# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The **Canada 1921 census** was a detailed enumeration of the Canadian population.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The census count was taken as at June 1, 1921.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The total population count was 8,788,483 representing a 22% increase over the 1911 census population count of 7,206,643.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The 1921 census was the sixth comprehensive decennial census since Canadian Confederation on July 1, 1867.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The previous census was the Northwest Provinces of Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba 1916 census and the following census was the Northwest Provinces of Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba 1926 census.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] Supplemental questionnaire for persons who were blind and deaf.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The five schedules contained a total of 565 questions.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The population questionnaire contained 35 questions with those on insanity and fertility having been dropped and a new question recording the birthplaces of the father and mother of each individual.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The most significant population growth took place in the Prairie provinces of Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Alberta, where the population count increased by 47%.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The census was conducted by the Dominion Bureau of Statistics formed in 1918 by the Statistics Act.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] Census fieldwork was carried out by 241 commissioners and 11,425 enumerators responsible for the corresponding numbers of census districts and subdistricts structured to correspond closely to federal electoral constituencies and polling subdivisions respectively.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] A special staff of up to 350 in Ottawa compiled the census results using mechanical tabulation methods.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] In 1955, the paper census schedules were destroyed after the population schedules were microfilmed.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] In accordance with the Statistics Act, the 1921 census returns were in the custody of Statistics Canada and the records were closed until 92 years after the taking of the census.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] In 2013, the records were opened for public use and transferred to Library and Archives Canada (LAC).
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] Ancestry.ca transcribed and indexed the data to facilitate advanced searches by individual Ancestry.ca subscribers, and in person at LAC and subscribing libraries, from late in 2013.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The census data was scheduled to be made available on the LAC website three years after being made available on the Ancestry.ca website.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The fully indexed online census data was launched by Ancestry.ca on October 29, 2013.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] The data is free to search, subject to registration on the Ancestry.ca website.
[src:canada/1921-canadian-census] On August 30, 2017, the results of the 1921 census were made available on the Library and Archives Canada website.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The **Newfoundland referendums of 1948** were two referendums that decided the political future of the Dominion of Newfoundland.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Before the referendums, Newfoundland was in debt and went through several delegations to determine whether the country would join Canada ("confederation"), remain under British rule or regain independence.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The voting for the referendums occurred on June 3 and July 22, 1948.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The eventual result was for Newfoundland to enter into Confederation, which it did on March 31, 1949, becoming the tenth province of Canada.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland was the first region in what would become Canada to be settled by Europeans, but was the last to obtain either a local representative government or responsible government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] In 1832, it received local representative government in the form of a locally elected body of officials overseen by a governor.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The British granted responsible government, in which the government is responsible to the legislature and elected officials occupy ministerial jobs, in 1855.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland did not send any delegates to the 1864 Charlottetown Conference, which was to discuss a union of Maritime colonies.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Later that year, Newfoundland attended the Quebec Conference, called by John A.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Macdonald to discuss a greater British North America union.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The two Newfoundland delegates, Frederick Carter and Ambrose Shea, returned in favour of a union with Canada.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] However, Confederation was highly unpopular with the Newfoundland public, and the Government of Newfoundland did not send representatives to the London Conference of 1866, in which the British government and the colonies agreed to the terms of the *British North America Act*.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Opponents of Confederation decisively won the 1869 Newfoundland general election.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] In 1907, Newfoundland became a self-governing Dominion separate from Canada.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] By the 1920s and the 1930s, Newfoundland was almost $40 million in debt, and on the verge of economic collapse.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] A commission recommended Newfoundland to be "given a rest from party politics" and to be administered by a special Commission of Government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Chaired by the governor, it would consist of three people from Newfoundland and three from the United Kingdom.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Backing the recommendation was the United Kingdom, which agreed to take on Newfoundland's debts.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Commission of Government began on February 16, 1934.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Prosperity returned when the Americans were invited to the island by Britain to set up military bases in 1941 to 1945.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The *American Bases Act* became law in Newfoundland on June 11, 1941.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland girls married American personnel by the thousands.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] In 1948 there was a short-lived but growing movement for some sort of economic union with the United States.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The British government, keen to cut expenditure after World War II, hoped that Newfoundland would decide to join the confederation and end the rule by commission.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland first asked Canada for help in a return to responsible government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] However, the response from the Canadian government was that it was not interested in helping Newfoundland economically unless Newfoundland joined Confederation.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Seeking a union with the United States was not a referendum option, despite the idea having some currency amongst locals.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] With the Cold War looming, U.S. interests in Newfoundland were centred primarily on its strategic importance to the defence of North America.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Americans' ability to maintain bases on the island satisfied those concerns — after receiving assurances that the Canadian government would honour the leases for bases on Newfoundland, the U.S.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] State Department had no further interest in the political future of Newfoundland.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Truman's administration had little incentive to pursue annexation.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] With respect to foreign policy, such a territorial ambition would have only served to antagonize two key allies.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The British government decided to let Newfoundlanders deliberate and choose their own future by calling a National Convention in 1946.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Fox, it consisted of 45 elected members, one of whom was the future first premier of Newfoundland, Joey Smallwood.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Convention set up committees to study where Newfoundland's future lay.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Many members assumed that the final decision was due near the end of their deliberations, but the timeline was upset when Smallwood moved that the Convention should send a delegation to Ottawa to discuss a union in October 1946.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] His motion was defeated, as it only received the support of 17 members, although the Convention later decided to send delegations to both London and Ottawa.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The London delegation, made up of so-called anti-confederates, preferred that Newfoundland become independent rather than join Canada.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The group left Newfoundland on April 25, 1947, and met with a British delegation headed by the Dominions Secretary, Viscount Addison.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The British response to the delegation was that it would give no economic help to Newfoundland if it returned to responsible government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The leader of the delegation from Newfoundland, Peter Cashin, gave an angry speech to the Convention on May 19 claiming, "A conspiracy existed to sell this country to the Dominion of Canada".
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Ottawa delegation, dominated by pro-confederates including Smallwood, preferred a union with Canada to independence.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The talks between them and Ottawa began on June 24, 1947 with the goal being to stay in Ottawa as long as needed to negotiate good terms for Newfoundland's entry.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Ottawa was reluctant at first because they felt that the delegation was not an official representation of the Dominion of Newfoundland, but the Federal Cabinet finally decided to begin negotiations on July 18.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] By mid-August, the agreement of draft terms was nearly complete.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] However, with the death of Frank Bridges, Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King's minister from New Brunswick, negotiations effectively ended.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] King refused further discussions until New Brunswick had representation, and so the delegation headed back to St.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Convention reconvened on October 10 and Smallwood presented his delegation's report, infuriating the anti-confederates.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Just as the Convention decided to debate the delegation's report, the draft terms from Ottawa arrived.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Ottawa offered to assume most of the debt, negotiate a tax agreement, and outlined which services would remain in the jurisdiction of the province.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland recommended that the British Government hold a referendum on Newfoundland's future.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] London agreed that a referendum was a good idea, and left it up to the Convention to decide what was to be on the ballot.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Originally, the Convention decided that only two choices were to be on the ballot: restoration of responsible government and the continuation of the Commission of Government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Smallwood moved on January 23, 1948, to add Confederation with Canada to the choices.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The debate ended at 5:30 a.m. on January 28, with the motion being defeated 29–16.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The British government intervened in March and overruled the Convention, deciding that Confederation with Canada would indeed be on the ballot.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] They did this after having concluded, "It would not be right that the people of Newfoundland should be deprived of an opportunity of considering the issue at the referendum".
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Three main factions actively campaigned during the lead up to the referendums.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] One faction, led by Smallwood, was the Confederate Association (CA) advocating entering into Confederation.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] They campaigned through a newspaper known as *The Confederate*.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Responsible Government League (RGL), led by Peter Cashin, advocated an independent Newfoundland with a return to responsible government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] They also had their own newspaper, *The Independent*.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] A third smaller Economic Union Party (EUP), led by Chesley Crosbie, advocated closer economic ties with the United States.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The first referendum took place on June 3, 1948.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Since none of the choices had gained over 50%, a second referendum with only the two most popular choices was scheduled for July 22, 1948.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Both sides recognized that more people had voted against responsible government than for it, which encouraged the CA and discouraged its opponents, although the RGL and EUP now became allies.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The confederates widely publicized the Roman Catholic Archbishop E.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Roche's strong opposition to confederation, and persuaded the Loyal Orange Association to advise Protestants to resist Catholic influence.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The CA also denounced anti-confederates as anti-British and pro-republican, and called confederation with Canada "British Union".
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Anti-confederates responded that "Confederation Means British Union With French Canada".
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] The Avalon Peninsula, the location of St.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] John's, supported responsible government in both referendums, while the rest of Newfoundland supported confederation.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] A majority of districts with mostly Catholic voters supported responsible government.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] As the results of the binding referendum were to join Canada, Newfoundland began to negotiate with Canada to enter into Confederation.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] After negotiations were completed, the British Government received the terms and the British North America Act 1949 was subsequently passed by the British Parliament and given Royal Assent.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland officially joined Canada at midnight, March 31, 1949.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] At the elections for the Newfoundland House of Assembly two months later, Smallwood's Liberal Party won and controlled the provincial government until the 1970s.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Newfoundland as a province secured some significant guarantees as a part of the union.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] As ruled by the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council in 1927, Canada agreed to put Labrador under the jurisdiction of Newfoundland, after some consideration.
[src:canada/1948-newfoundland-referendums] Such commitments carried over to other areas as well, such as a ferry between Channel-Port aux Basques and North Sydney, and a guarantee that Newfoundland would be able to continue to manufacture and sell margarine, a very controversial product at the time.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Montreal was awarded the rights to the 1976 Games at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam on May 12, 1970, over the bids of Moscow and Los Angeles.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] It is the only Summer Olympic Games to be held in Canada.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto hosted the 1976 Summer Paralympics the same year as the Montreal Olympics, also the only Summer Paralympics to be held in Canada.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Calgary and Vancouver later hosted the Winter Olympic Games in 1988 and 2010, respectively.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] This was the first of two consecutive Olympic games held in North America, followed by the 1980 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals, with the Eastern Bloc having seven countries in the top 10 of the medal table.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The vote occurred at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam, Netherlands on May 12, 1970.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] While Los Angeles and Moscow were viewed as the favourites, given that they represented the world's two main powers, many of the smaller and neutral countries supported Montreal as an underdog and as a relatively neutral site for the Games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was eliminated after the first round, and Montreal won over Moscow in the second round.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Moscow and Los Angeles would go on to host the next two Summer Games, 1980 and 1984 Summer Olympics, respectively, which were also marked by political boycotts (for instance, the U.S.-led boycott of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979).
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] One blank vote was cast in the second and final round.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet state media accused the IOC of political corruption following the vote, accusing them of facilitating the Soviet Union's loss.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto had made its third attempt for the Olympics, as did Hamilton.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Still, they failed to win the support of the Canadian Olympic Committee, which selected Montreal instead.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Another candidate was the Italian city of Florence, which announced that it would withdraw from contention two months before the vote.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Robert Bourassa, then the Premier of Quebec, asked Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau to advise Canada's monarch Elizabeth II to attend the opening of the games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] However, Bourassa later became unsettled about how unpopular the move might be with sovereigntists in the province, annoying Trudeau, who had already made arrangements.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] René Lévesque, the leader of the Parti Québécois at the time, sent his own letter to Buckingham Palace, asking the Queen to refuse her prime minister's request, but she did not oblige Lévesque as he was out of his jurisdiction in offering advice to the Sovereign.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, Trudeau, succumbing to pressure from the People's Republic of China, issued an order barring Taiwan from participating as China in the 1976 Montreal Olympics, although it was technically a matter for the IOC.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] His action strained relations with the United States – from President Ford to future President Carter and the press.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Trudeau's action was widely condemned as having brought shame on Canada by succumbing to political pressure to keep the Taiwanese delegation from competing under its name.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The mascot was a beaver named Amik, whose name was chosen after a national competition.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study* estimates the outturn cost of the Montreal 1976 Summer Olympics at US$6.1 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 720% in real terms.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] *Indirect* capital costs are not included, such as those for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, or for hotel upgrades or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The cost overrun for Montreal 1976 is the highest cost overrun on record for any Olympics.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The cost and cost overrun for Montreal 1976 compares with costs of US$4.6 billion and a cost overrun of 51% for Rio de Janeiro in 2016 and $15 billion and 76% for London in 2012.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games from 1960 to 2016 was $5.2 billion in 2015 dollars, and the average cost overrun was 176%.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] French architect Roger Taillibert, who designed the Olympic stadium, recounted in his 2000 book *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* that he and Mayor Drapeau tried hard to buy off Desjardins, even taking him to a lunch at the exclusive Ritz-Carlton hotel in a vain attempt to end the "delays".
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] He suggests that Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa ultimately made a secret deal to buy off Desjardins, which allowed work to proceed.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Taillibert wrote in *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* "If the Olympic Games took place, it was thanks to Dede Desjardins.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] What irony!" The delays and scandals caused Quebec premier Robert Bourassa to take over the preparations of the games in November 1975.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Vélodrome de Montréal, which was scheduled for opening in 1974, was finally completed in June 1976, a month before the opening ceremony.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 1976 Summer Olympic Games was held at the incomplete Olympic Stadium in Montreal, Quebec on Saturday afternoon, July 17, 1976, in front of an audience of some 73,000 in the stadium and an estimated half billion watching on television.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Following an air show by the Canadian Forces Air Command's Snowbirds aerobatic flight demonstration squadron in the sunny skies above the stadium, the ceremony officially began at 3:00 pm with a trumpet fanfare and the arrival of Elizabeth II, as Queen of Canada.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Queen entered the Royal Box with her consort, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, and her son, Prince Andrew.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] (Her daughter, Princess Anne, was competing as a member of Great Britain's equestrian team.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The parade of athletes began moments later with the arrival of the Greek team, and concluded with the entrance of the Canadian team.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] All other teams entered the stadium according to French alphabetical order (as the host city's main language).
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The ceremony was marked by the adorning of Israel's flag with a black mourning ribbon, in memory of the eleven athletes and coaches killed by Palestinian terrorists at the previous Summer Olympic Games in Munich four years earlier.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Although most would eventually boycott the Games in the days to follow, a number of African delegations did march in the parade.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Much of the music performed for the parade was arranged by Victor Vogel and was inspired by late Quebecois composer André Mathieu.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Immediately following the parade, a troupe of 80 female dancers dressed in white (representing the 80th anniversary of the revival of the Olympic Games) performed a brief dance in the outline of the Olympic rings.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Following that came the official speeches, first by Roger Rousseau, head of the Montreal Olympic organizing committee, and Lord Killanin.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Her Majesty was then invited to proclaim the Games open, which she did, first in French, then in English.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Accompanied by the Olympic Hymn, the Olympic flag was carried into the stadium and hoisted at the west end of the stadium.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The flag was carried by eight men and hoisted by four women, representing the ten provinces and two territories (at the time) of Canada.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] As the flag was hoisted, an all-male choir performed an a cappella version of the Olympic Hymn.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Once the flag was hosted, a troupe of Bavarian dancers representing Munich, host of the previous Summer Olympics, entered the stadium with the Antwerp flag.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Following a brief dance, that flag was then passed from the Mayor of Munich to the IOC President and then to the Mayor of Montreal.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Next came a presentation of traditional Québécois folk dancers.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The two troupes merged in dance together to the strains of "Vive le Compagnie" and exited the stadium with the Antwerp Flag, which would be displayed at Montreal City Hall until the opening of the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Three cannons were then fired, as the 80-member troupe of female dancers unfolded special crates that released doves and ribbons in the five Olympic colours.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Another trumpet fanfare announced the arrival of the Olympic Flame.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The torch was carried by 15-year-olds Stéphane Préfontaine and Sandra Henderson, chosen as representatives of the unity within Canada's linguistic heritage.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] This would also be the first time two people would light the Olympic flame.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The duo would make a lap of the stadium and then climbed a staircase on a special dais at the centre of the stadium to set the Olympic flame alight in a temporary white aluminum cauldron.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The flame was later transported to a more permanent cauldron just outside the running track to burn throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] A choir then performed the Olympic Cantata as onlookers admired the Olympic flame.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The "Youth of Canada" took to the track to perform a colourful choreographed segment with flags, ribbons and a variety of rhythmic gymnast performers.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The flag bearers of each team then circled around the speaker's dais as Pierre St-Jean recited the Athletes' Oath and Maurice Forget recited the Judges' Oath, in English and in French, with right hands over their hearts and Canadian flags clutched in their left.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Finally, a choral performance of "O Canada" in both French and English marked the close of the opening ceremony, as the announcers concluded with a declaration of the Games motto: 'Vive les Jeux de Montreal!
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Montreal ceremony would be the last of its kind in Summer Games, as future Olympic ceremonies, beginning with the new Olympic Charter were reinforced before the 1980 Summer Olympics, would become more focused on the host country's culture.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Because of the Munich massacre, security at these games was visible.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The extensive security measures included the requirement for all workers to hold a valid accreditation.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Surveillance of acoustics was installed in the Olympic Village where athletes were accommodated.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Furthermore, a systematic installation of closed-circuit television (CCTV) was attempted for the first time in the history of the Olympic games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] There was a desire by the IOC's program commission to reduce the number of competitors and a number of recommendations were put to the IOC's executive board on February 23, 1973, which were all accepted.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Rowing was the only sport where the number of competitors was increased, and women were admitted for the first time in Olympic history.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Four nations made their first Summer Olympic appearance in Montreal: Andorra (which had its overall Olympic debut a few months before in Innsbruck Winter Olympics), Antigua and Barbuda (as *Antigua*), Cayman Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of athletes from each nation that competed at the Games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1976 Games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Canada placed 27th with only 11 medals in total, none of them being gold.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Canada remains the only host nation of a Summer Olympics to fail to win at least one gold medal.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] It also did not win any gold medals at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] However, Canada went on to win the most gold medals at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Games were dominated by the Soviet Bloc, with the USSR and its satellites occupying seven out of top ten places in the medal standings.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Twenty-nine countries boycotted the Games due to the refusal of the IOC to ban New Zealand, after the New Zealand national rugby union team had toured South Africa earlier in 1976.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott was led by Congolese official Jean-Claude Ganga.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Some of the boycotting nations (including Morocco, Cameroon and Egypt) had already participated, however, and withdrew after the first few days.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Senegal and Ivory Coast were the only African countries that competed throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Elsewhere, Afghanistan, Albania, Burma, Iraq, Guyana, Sri Lanka and Syria also opted to join the Congolese-led boycott.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] South Africa had been banned from the Olympics since 1964 due to its apartheid policies.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Other countries, such as El Salvador and Zaire, did not participate in Montreal for purely economic reasons.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] An unrelated boycott of the Montreal Games was the main issue between the Republic of China (ROC) and the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The ROC team withdrew from the games when Canada's Liberal government under Pierre Trudeau told it that the name "Republic of China" was not permissible at the Games because Canada had officially recognized the PRC in 1970.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Canada attempted a compromise by allowing the ROC the continued use of its national flag and anthem in the Montreal Olympic activities; the ROC refused.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] In 1979 the IOC established in the Nagoya Resolution that the PRC agreed to participate in IOC activities if the Republic of China was referred to as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Another boycott would occur before the ROC would accept the provisions of the 1979 resolution.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Researchers from Germany in 2013 reported that West Germany had a state-sponsored doping program, and speculated it was in response to doping in East Germany which had existed for decades.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] ABC Sports paid US$25-million for television broadcast rights in the United States, and produced 76.5 hours of coverage.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports budgeted less than CAD$2-million and produced 169 hours of coverage, compared to 14 hours of programming at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The network expanded its coverage in 1976, when convinced there would be increased media interest from Canadians.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] When the network was criticized for spending taxpayer dollars, executive producer Bob Moir toured the country to explain the project and boasted that, "the biggest team in Montreal will be the CBC team...
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] It will be bigger than the Canadian Olympic team".
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports had 245 people on its crew, and aired from 9 am until 11 pm daily, taking breaks only for newscasts.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Ted Reynolds and Lloyd Robertson co-hosted coverage of the opening ceremonies.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, CBC Sports began its practice of talking live with athletes immediately after events, and built a studio for the interviews.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] CBC broadcasters were given information kits on the athletes, prepared by Jack Sullivan, the former sports editor of The Canadian Press.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The legacy of the Montreal Olympics is complex.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Many citizens regard the Olympiad as a financial disaster for the city as it faced debts for 30 years after the Games had finished.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The retractable roof of the Olympic Stadium never properly worked and on several occasions has torn, prompting the stadium to be closed for extended periods of time for repairs.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The failure of the Montreal Expos baseball club is largely blamed on the failure of the Olympic Stadium to transition into an effective and popular venue for the club – given the massive capacity of the stadium, it often looked unimpressive even with regular crowds in excess of 20,000 spectators.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Quebec provincial government took over construction when it became evident in 1975 that work had fallen far behind schedule.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Work was still ongoing just weeks before the opening date, and the tower was not built.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Mayor Jean Drapeau had confidently predicted in 1970 that "the Olympics can no more have a deficit than a man can have a baby", but the debt racked up to a billion dollars that the Quebec government mandated the city pay in full.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] This would prompt cartoonist Aislin to draw a pregnant Drapeau on the telephone saying, "Allo, Morgentaler?" in reference to a Montreal abortion provider.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was designed by French architect Roger Taillibert.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] It is often nicknamed "The Big O" as a reference to both its name and to the doughnut-shape of the permanent component of the stadium's roof, though "The Big Owe" has been used to reference the astronomical cost of the stadium and the 1976 Olympics as a whole.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] It has never had an effective retractable roof, and the tower (called the Montreal Tower) was completed only eleven years after the Olympic Games, in 1987.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] In December 2006 the stadium's costs were finally paid in full.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The total expenditure (including repairs, renovations, construction, interest, and inflation) amounted to C$1.61 billion.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Today the stadium lacks a permanent tenant, as the Montreal Alouettes and Montreal Expos have moved, though it does host some individual games of the Alouettes as well as CF Montréal (formerly the Montreal Impact).
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] One of the streets surrounding the Olympic Stadium was renamed to honour Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the Olympics.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott by African nations over the inclusion of New Zealand, whose rugby team had played in South Africa that year, was a contributing factor in the massive protests and civil disobedience that occurred during the 1981 Springbok Tour of New Zealand.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Official sporting contacts between South Africa and New Zealand did not occur again until after the fall of apartheid.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] Australia's failure to win a gold medal led the country to create the Australian Institute of Sport.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] In 2016, the 40th anniversary celebrations were held.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] In conjunction with the celebrations, the 2016 Quebec Games were held.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The games were the subject of *Games of the XXI Olympiad (Jeux de la XXIe olympiade)*, a 1977 documentary film by Jean Beaudin, Marcel Carrière, Georges Dufaux and Jean-Claude Labrecque.
[src:canada/1976-summer-olympics] The 1976 games were also an inspiration for Australian band Black Cab's double album of 2014 entitled *Games of the XXI Olympiad*.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The **1980 Quebec independence referendum** was the first referendum in Quebec on the place of Quebec within Canada and whether Quebec should pursue a path toward sovereignty.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The referendum was called by Quebec's Parti Québécois (PQ) government, which advocated secession from Canada.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The province-wide referendum took place on May 20, and the proposal to pursue secession was defeated by a 59.56 per cent to 40.44 per cent margin.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] A second referendum on sovereignty, which was held in 1995, also rejected pursuing secession, albeit by a much smaller margin (50.58% to 49.42%).
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Quebec, a province since Canadian Confederation in 1867, has always been the sole majority French-speaking province.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Since Canada's creation, tensions have existed between the French and English parts of the country.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] With English being the only national language until 1969, French Canadians in Quebec saw bilingualism as a “one-way road”, with French speakers expected to learn English to cater to Anglophones both in Quebec and the rest of the country.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Roman Catholic Church held power over everything from educational to welfare institutions in the province, with Quebec citizens having to pay tithe taxes to the Church.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] As industrialization grew the size of the working middle class, power remained in the hands of English speakers.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In Montreal, many mayors through the nineteenth and twentieth centuries did not speak French.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] This led to what The Canadian Journal of Economics and Political Science called "a Montreal elite largely imported, overall Anglo-Saxon, and dominated by business matters".
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Across Quebec, business was conducted in English, with French speakers never controlling more than 20% of businesses throughout the 1900s.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] This constant subordination of French Canadians in Quebec led to the Quiet Revolution, characterized by the effective secularization of society and the creation of a welfare state (*état-providence*).
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] It also caused a realignment of provincial politics into federalist and sovereigntist factions, the latter calling for the separation of Quebec from Canada and its establishment as a sovereign nation state.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] A prominent sovereigntist was René Lévesque, who helped found the Parti Québécois (PQ) with like-minded separatists.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The PQ proposed "sovereignty-association", a proposal for Quebec to be a sovereign nation-state while requiring (hence the hyphen) an economic partnership with what remained of Canada.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The PQ had intended to declare independence upon forming government, citing the principle of parliamentary supremacy.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] This was changed in the party platform after internal lobbying by Claude Morin to a referendum strategy to better allow such a declaration to be internationally recognized.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The PQ won the 1976 election in a surprise rout of the governing Quebec Liberals of Robert Bourassa on a general platform of good government and the promise of holding a referendum on sovereignty-association during their first term.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In government, the PQ implemented a number of popular reforms to longstanding issues in the province, while emphasizing its nationalist credentials with laws such as Bill 101, which reinforced French as the province's official language.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The bill controls everything from street signs to education to internal business communications, and essentially gives everyone the right to live in Quebec without knowing English.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] While the bill was popular in French circles as it finally affirmed their language rights, it added to the tension in English communities.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] With anything English-only, even product labels, effectively banned, Bill 101 may have contributed to growing Anglophone migration out of Quebec, and one Anglophone paper at the time said Bill 101 made Quebec a “police state”.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The PQ's efforts were in philosophical conflict with the federal Liberal government of Pierre Elliot Trudeau, an opponent of sovereignty who instead urged Quebecers to seek empowerment at the federal level through reforms that provided for bilingualism and protection for individual rights.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau, an effective campaigner whose party had dominated federal politics in Quebec for over 80 years, was considered such a formidable opponent that Lévesque refused to implement a referendum while Trudeau remained in office.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In the 1979 federal election, the Liberals were narrowly defeated by the Progressive Conservatives led by Joe Clark, whose platform had included a more accommodating approach to constitutional negotiations with the provinces.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Clark's minority government made a point to not have the federal government be involved in the referendum, leaving the task of representing federalist voices to Claude Ryan, the new leader of the Quebec Liberal Party.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] On June 21, 1979, Lévesque announced the promised referendum would occur in the spring of 1980, and that the question would be announced before Christmas.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] On November 1, 1979, the Quebec government made public its constitutional proposal in a white paper entitled *Québec-Canada: A New Deal.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Québec Government Proposal for a New Partnership Between Equals: Sovereignty-Association*.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Three days afterward, Trudeau announced his return as leader of the Liberals.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The referendum question was a subject of much internal debate amongst the Parti Québécois caucus.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] *Pur et durs* such as Finance Minister Jacques Parizeau preferred a simple question on the entirety of the proposal.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Lévesque came to the view that, as sovereignty-association would by necessity require negotiations with the Government of Canada, the government of Quebec should be treated as a legal agent and require ratification of its final decision.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] A significant debate arose as to whether a "question" under the *Referendum Act* could have more than one sentence: the final compromise was to use semicolons.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Lévesque, while noting its cumbersome nature, stated that it was transparent and could be easily understood.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Liberals presented their constitutional proposal, known as the "Beige Paper" on January 10, 1980, which advocated a decentralized Canadian federation.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] While generally viewed as detailed and competent, the report did not make much impact on the federal election, and was attacked by the PQ as vague and insubstantial.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Ryan, who disliked the federal Liberals, refused to endorse either Trudeau or Clark.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] On February 18, 1980, the federal Liberals won a majority in the House of Commons, and Trudeau returned as Prime Minister.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau announced Jean Chrétien, his most trusted lieutenant, as having responsibilities for the federal response to the referendum.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Television had recently been introduced to the Quebec National Assembly, and the legislative debate on the referendum question was scheduled for prime time live viewing on March 4, 1980.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The debate lasted two weeks, and the result was a smashing PQ success and a disaster for the provincial Liberals.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The PQ Cabinet, coordinated by House Leader Claude Charron, provided detailed outlines of their files and the benefits they said sovereignty would provide them.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Liberals provided quick and taunting retorts regarding the referendum question that would normally be heard on the legislative floor, but which appeared to be flippant and insubstantial compared to the lengthy and detailed speeches of PQ members to television viewers.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Liberals seemed to lack preparation and Ryan, unaware of the television cameras, was caught yawning on a few occasions during Liberal interventions.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Payette then stated that Ryan wanted a Quebec full of "Yvettes" and that his wife, Madeline Ryan, was an Yvette.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The personal attack prompted a furious editorial by prominent journalist Lise Bissonnette, who sarcastically contrasted Payette's televised exploits with Mme Ryan's accomplishments in the private and public sector.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Payette apologized during the legislative debate, but the remark and editorial sparked a movement.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] On March 30, a group of 1,700 women, including Madeline Ryan, held the *brunch des Yvettes* at the Château Frontenac in Quebec City.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] On April 15, Lévesque announced before the National Assembly the referendum would occur on May 20, 1980.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The same day, on the opening of the House of Commons, Trudeau announced that the Government of Canada would not negotiate sovereignty-association under any circumstances, as he considered the question too vague and the Canadian government's authority too uncertain to do so.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] He also stated that the question was too vague to give Lévesque and the PQ any mandate to declare independence, making any result from a "Yes" vote impossible; in contrast, he offered that a "No" vote would lead to constitutional change.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] His position was supported by Clark and national NDP leader Ed Broadbent.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The "Yes" campaign was, in the initial stages, low key.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] It focused on gaining broad acceptance of sovereignty-association through specialized "regroupments" that would be presented with special certificates at ceremonies led by Lévesque and other cabinet ministers.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The regroupments were seen as an attempt to show broad support for the movement and create conversations at the ground level, however, the attempt to create them in some heavily Federalist professions, such as lawyers, prompted a severe backlash.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The "No" campaign, led by Ryan, was run as a traditional election campaign, with Ryan campaigning during the day and making speeches in local hockey arenas across rural Quebec.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Controversially, the Canadian government became involved on its own accord in the referendum despite the provisions of the provincial *Referendum Act*, which tightly restricted all campaigning to the designated "Yes" and "No" committees with set budgets.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Canadian government politicians made appearances coordinated by Minister of Justice Jean Chrétien and Marc Lalonde, mainly speculating on the economic uncertainty a "Yes" vote could bring.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Chrétien argued that prominent PQ member Claude Morin would sacrifice Canada's oil and national gas price to drive in an ambassadors' Cadillac.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Lalonde argued that old age pensions were directly threatened by a "Yes" vote.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Though initially reluctant, Ryan started to accept and welcome the Canadian government's help, and continued to speak across Quebec.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The referendum prompted an unheard-of political mobilization, and the campaign was seen as a traumatic event in Quebec, as the hard choice between "Yes" and "No" shattered the nationalist consensus that had existed since the Quiet Revolution.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] On May 14, six days before the vote, Trudeau made his final appearance at a packed Paul Sauvé Arena, where the PQ had celebrated their victory in 1976.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau attacked the "Yes" campaign for not asking a clear question, and stated that a "Yes" vote was a dead end, given that the rest of Canada was not bound by the question and that it was too vague to pursue independence if negotiations were refused.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau then stated that he would interpret a vote for the "No" as a mandate to renew federalism and change the constitution, putting his MPs' seats on the line if he were to fail to keep this promise.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Addressing himself to Canadians outside Quebec on behalf of his MPs, Trudeau challenged English Canada that change would have to occur and that the referendum could not be interpreted as an endorsement of the status quo.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] After this Trudeau hit an emotional high note, invoking a remark by Lévesque days earlier that he was showing his "Elliott" side during the campaign.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau detailed the story of his parents, who had both had many ancestors in Quebec, and remarked that his full name was both a Québécois and a Canadian name.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau then began to list members of the Parti Québécois who had Irish or English last names.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The speech, which prompted Morin to wonder if his mind was changed, was seen as the death knell of the "Yes" camp, despite Lévesque's attempts to cast doubt over Trudeau's words.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] After the lopsided defeat, a visibly emotional Lévesque addressed his supporters, many of whom were shown on screen in tears at the result.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Lévesque began with, "My dear friends, if I understand you correctly, you're saying: 'until next time'".
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] While calling the Canadian government's involvement in the campaign "scandalously immoral", he emphasized that the result must be accepted and that it was now the Canadian government's responsibility to provide the promised changes to the constitution.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] He ended asking the audience to sing "*Gens du Pays*" for him, as he did not have any voice left.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Claude Ryan's speech was later in the evening.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] After refusing to let Jean Chrétien use the microphone to address those gathered, he proceeded to demand an election be called and listed every riding that had voted for the "No" side.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The speech was generally seen as callous and harsh, especially after the emotional crowd scenes broadcast during Lévesque's speech.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau addressed the country afterward with a more conciliatory tone, emphasizing the need for unity after the hurt feelings and strained friendships that had been caused by the referendum.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The next morning, Chrétien was tasked with creating a provincial consensus.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In Montreal, reactions were divided and emotional.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Many predicted the referendum would result in violence and an early election.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Shortly after results were released, a small riot of “Yes” voters marched through Westmount, a wealthy English neighbourhood, causing minor property damage.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The aftermath of the referendum was filled with uncertainty, with sociologist Maurice Penard predicting more violence and an early election.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] After the referendum, Trudeau acted upon his promise by calling together the provincial premiers in a first ministers' conference.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The meeting showed signs of deadlock, and Lévesque surprised observers by uniting with the dissident premiers, who warmly received his decentralist views.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Facing a lack of cooperation from the premiers, Trudeau then announced his intention to unilaterally patriate the constitution from the United Kingdom and have a charter of rights and constitutional amending formula approved by national referendum.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In the meantime, there was a provincial election in Quebec.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Despite a brief post-referendum malaise, the PQ easily defeated Ryan's Liberals in the 1981 provincial election, campaigning both on their governing record and against Trudeau's intentions.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Notably, the PQ did not promise to hold a second referendum.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The federal government, still interested in proceeding unilaterally, sought an opinion on whether it was legally entitled to do so from the Supreme Court of Canada.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Supreme Court ruled that any constitutional changes, including patriation of the constitution, could be made unilaterally under the letter of the law, but, by non-binding convention, "a substantial degree of provincial consent was required".
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The Supreme Court's decision prompted a final meeting among the first ministers.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Lévesque abandoned the Gang of Eight and opted to join Trudeau in advocating immediate patriation with the promise of a future referendum on the other matters.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The other premiers, loath to be seen arguing against the charter of rights that was included in Trudeau's proposed constitutional changes, formulated a compromise proposal with Jean Chrétien that was acceptable to the Canadian government.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The compromise came during the Kitchen Meeting, which took place after Lévesque had left for the evening.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In Quebec, that night has sometimes been called the "Night of the Long Knives".
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] As a result of the compromise between the premiers (other than Lévesque) and the federal government, the government patriated the Canadian constitution in the Constitution Act, 1982 without support from Lévesque or Quebec's National Assembly.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The result was a shattering defeat for the PQ, especially after the Quebec government's loss in its Quebec Veto Reference case.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The National Assembly of Quebec, compared to its position in 1976, actually lost power under Lévesque and the PQ.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Historical debate would centre on whether Trudeau's advocacy and agreement on patriation were in accord with or in contravention of his commitments made in his speech at the Paul Sauvé Arena.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Trudeau defended his actions by stating he had kept his promise to deliver a new constitution that resided entirely within Canada and an embedded Charter of Rights.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Quebec nationalists argue that this is an overly literal view of his words and that, in context to a Québécois audience, Trudeau had promised that Quebec would be given a status in accordance with a decentralized view of federalism, or his MPs would resign.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] In 1984, Brian Mulroney led the Progressive Conservatives to victory nationally, having committed during the campaign to try to find a way to accommodate Quebec's objections to the constitution.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Lévesque pledged to take the risk of trying to work towards a deal with Mulroney.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] This led to a split in the PQ and subsequently Lévesque's resignation from politics in 1985.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] After the PQ defeat by the Liberals of Robert Bourassa, the Mulroney government began negotiations with Quebec to find a deal that would be acceptable to all provinces.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The 1987 Meech Lake Accord and the 1992 Charlottetown Accord, despite receiving unanimous consent among the provincial premiers, each failed in dramatic public fashion, reviving the sovereignty movement.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] The PQ returned to office, led by hard-line separatist and former Finance Minister Jacques Parizeau, in 1994.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] Parizeau called a second sovereignty referendum of 1995, which featured a more direct question.
[src:canada/1980-quebec-referendum] That referendum failed by a margin of less than 0.6%.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The **1988 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **XV Olympic Winter Games** (French: *XVes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Calgary 1988** were a multi-sport event held from February 13 to 28, 1988, with Calgary, Alberta, as the main host city.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This marks the most recent time that two consecutive Olympic Games were hosted in North America (with the 1984 Summer Olympic Games hosted in Los Angeles, California, United States).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympic Games to be held for 15 days, like the counterpart Summer Olympic Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The majority of the events took place in Calgary itself.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the snow events were shared by Nakiska ski resort in Kananaskis Country at the west of the city and the Canmore Nordic Centre Provincial Park in the town of Canmore.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the last Winter Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1988, a record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOC) sent a total of 1,424 athletes to these Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These Winter Olympics would be the last attended for both the Soviet Union and East Germany NOCs.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Just like the 1976 Summer Olympics, host country Canada failed again to win a gold medal on their home soil (they won three gold medals in demonstration events, but these are not included in the official medal table).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Finnish ski jumper, Matti Nykänen, and the Dutch speed skater, Yvonne van Gennip, won three individual gold medals each.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics were also remembered for the "heroic failure" of both the British ski jumper, Michael Edwards, and the debut of the Jamaica national bobsleigh team.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Both of them became subjects of major feature films about their participation in these Games: *Cool Runnings* by Walt Disney Pictures in 1993 and *Eddie the Eagle* by 20th Century Fox in 2016.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At approximately C$829 million, the Calgary Games were the most expensive Olympics ever held at the time, as all the necessary infrastructure was built from scratch.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The facilities that were built for these Winter Olympics helped the host region to turn into the heart of Canada's elite winter sports program, under the tutelage of WinSport.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the Games, their legacy still standing and in constant use, as the five purpose-built venues for those Games are now used for training and hosting various winter sporting events every year.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These policies helped Canada develop into one of the top nations in Winter Olympics competition.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The climax of this effort was the overall first-place finish at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, Canada.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary made its fourth attempt at hosting the Winter Games when it bid for the 1988 Winter Olympic Games, which also marked Canada's seventh bid for the Winter Olympic Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Montreal made the first Canadian bid for the Winter Games in 1956 and won the rights to host the 1976 Summer Olympics, and Vancouver made attempts to host the 1976 and 1980 Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary, alongside neighbouring Banff, under the leadership of the Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA), submitted bids for the Winter Games in 1964, 1968, and 1972.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, CODA went dormant in 1966 after losing three consecutive bids.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, Frank King and Bob Niven of Calgary's Booster Club took over the organization's leadership and revived CODA.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King and Niven consulted former Olympic Sprinter and CODA founder, Ernie McCullough, and politician Arthur Ryan Smith, who had worked on previous bids, for guidance on the project.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In October 1979, CODA secured the Canadian Olympic Association's (COA) support for Canada's official bid to host the 1988 Winter Olympics, winning over a competing bid by Vancouver with a vote of 27–9.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary's bid was at the time the most ambitious for the Winter Olympics ever, as the city lacked winter sports facilities and almost everything would have to be built from scratch.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA proposed constructing all new venues, arguing that if Calgary was awarded the Games, Canada's inventory of training facilities would increase significantly.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Vancouver bidding committee argued that Calgary's bid represented a "Big-ticket Games" idea, and estimated to cost nearly three times what Vancouver was expected to pay to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Vancouver's bid was based on already developed infrastructure, including the Expo 86 precinct, the Pacific Coliseum and Whistler Blackcomb, which later served as the basis for the successful 2010 Winter Olympics bid and the later unsuccessful 2030 Winter Olympics bid.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA then spent two years building local support for the megaproject, selling CA$5 memberships to approximately 80,000 of Calgary's 600,000 residents.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary also secured CA$270 million in funding from the federal (CA$200 million) and provincial governments.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Some civic leaders, including then-mayor Ralph Klein, travelled around the world to lobby IOC delegates.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The arrival of the National Hockey League's (NHL) newly relocated Calgary Flames from Atlanta in 1980 drove the city to construct a new multi-use arena that would later be named the Olympic Saddledome, demonstrating to the IOC Calgary's determination to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic bid itself emphasized the unique cultural and natural characteristics who mark the Calgary Metropolitan Region and the Alberta Province and also canadian prairies landscapes, as a perfect places for hosting the Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At the bidding documents, the city was marketed with a capitalist, oil-driven and vibrant economy that also had mountain playgrounds, extensive wilderness, and a rodeo culture.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When the two images of Calgary and Alberta were brought together, they seemed to be contrasting; however, they complemented each other as part of extensive and intense bidding lobby process.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary was one of three finalists during the 1988 Winter Olympics bid process.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The other two were Falun, Sweden, and Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Italian town (comune) had before hosted the 1956 Winter Olympics and was seen by many as the favorite.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The vote was held on September 30, 1981, in Baden-Baden, West Germany, during the 84th IOC Session and 11th Olympic Congress.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After Cortina d'Ampezzo was eliminated in the first round of balloting, Calgary won in the second and final round of balloting over Falun, by a margin of 17 votes.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The announcement of CODA's victory sent the delegates in Baden-Baden and Calgary residents into singing and dancing.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also made then Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, burst openly into tears in front of the cameras.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Later, Ralph Klein sang a rendition of Mac Davis' *It's Hard to Be Humble*.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympics awarded to Canada and the second Olympic Games overall, following the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Cortina d'Ampezzo, along with Milan, would get to host the 2026 Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pelle noted that once the Games were awarded to Calgary, the cultural and community aspects of the bid were pushed aside by the newly formed Calgary Olympic organizing committee called the *Olympiques Calgary Olympics '88* (OCO'88).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It then proceeded to take on a "vigorous, resilient, and impersonal corporate business strategy" based in the work made by Los Angeles 1984 Organizing Committee (LAOCOG) toward the planning and operation of the Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Bill Pratt was a former general contractor who took over as OCO'88 president in 1983.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He was the main manager that oversaw the construction of the Olympic megaproject.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Donald Jacques, a former general manager of the Calgary Exhibition and Stampede, once said, "Because of him, everything was built on time and on budget." However, Bill Pratt was controversial by rubbing many of his colleagues the wrong way.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One former co-worker once predicted back in 1983: "He will get everything built.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There may not be many (of us) left around to enjoy it, but he'll get it done." His relations with the news media were also strained at times.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He had barely settled into his new position when the Calgary press media began criticizing OCO'88 for excessive secrecy and for awarding Olympic contracts to Calgary's PR firm Francis Williams and Johnson Ltd.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pratt was a director of that firm, before accepting the organizing committee job.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 had insisted that there was no conflict of interest involved in the whole process.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Pratt declared: "I have been nailed for a lot, but that does not bother me.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the 1988 Winter Olympics bid was won in 1981, OCO'88 made a new technical assessment and had to re-plan all the originally proposed competition venues except for the few that already existed and were within the campus of the University of Calgary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] McMahon Stadium, the primary outdoor facility used mainly by the Canadian Football League's (CFL) Calgary Stampeders and inside of the University of Calgary and had originally been chosen to host only the opening ceremonies and the Saddledome was chosen to be the place of the closing ceremonies.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] But with the constant revisions of the project, the later addition of 4 more days in competition and mainly the gigantic demands for tickets, the Organizing Committee decided to move the closing ceremony to the Stadium which held twice the capacity of the Saddledome.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The last time that the two Winter Olympic ceremonies were held at the same venue was at the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley, California.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics' five main all-purpose venues were created at a significant cost at that time.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three of them are located within Calgary and the other two are located west of the city.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Olympic Saddledome was planned to be the main venue of the games, hosting ice hockey and figure skating finals.This arena is also part of Stampede Park and was expected to cost C$83 million, but a cost overrun pushed it to nearly C$100 million and caused a nine-month delay.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Second, the Olympic Oval was built on the campus of the University of Calgary for C$40 million.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Third, Canada Olympic Park (formerly called the *Paskapoo Ski Hill*) was renovated for C$200 million and is located on the western outskirts of Calgary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This most expensive venue of these Winter Olympics hosted the men's bobsleigh, luge, and men's ski jumping and its portion of the Nordic combined events.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, it hosted some events of the demonstration sport of freestyle skiing.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From the west of Calgary, the other two main all-purpose venues were built at the foothills of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Canmore Nordic Centre was 90% funded by the province of Alberta, for C$17.3 million.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located beside the town of Canmore and it hosted cross-country skiing, plus its men's portion of the Nordic combined, and the men's biathlon events.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was projected that the area could become a year-round destination for Albertans, by facilitating and accelerate Canmore's economic transition away from coal mining to tourist attraction.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the Nakiska (*Cree* meaning "to meet") ski resort was the most controversial and polemic complex built for these Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located on Mount Allan (inside Kananaskis Country) and it hosted the alpine skiing events.It cost around C$25 million to Alberta government funds.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This venue drew a lot of criticisms because of the various environmental concerns, the rejection by International Ski Federation (FIS) of slopes for each of the 10 events in the program and the use of artificial snow due to the lack of natural snow on that season.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the first inspections, the International Ski Federation (FIS) officials noted the venue's lack of technical difficulties needed for the Olympic competition.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, these FIS delegates proposed some major changes in the slopes in an action to cause bigger difficulties.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These modifications were met with praise from Olympic alpine skiing competitors.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Like at Canada Olympic Park, this venue also hosted some freestyle skiing events as a demonstration sport.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three other existing facilities served as secondary competition venues for the Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The first one, was the Max Bell Centre hosted the demonstration sports of curling and short track speed skating.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Father David Bauer Olympic Arena and the Stampede Corral shared the functions of secondary venues for the ice hockey tournament and the figure skating preliminaries.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Though the Stampede Corral did not support the International Ice Hockey Federation's (IIHF) standard-sized Olympic ice surface, OCO'88 was able to convince the IIHF to sanction the ice rink for Olympic competition, in exchange for a C$1.2 million payment.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) entered athletes at the 1988 Winter Olympics, with eight more NOCs than any other previous Olympic Winter Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] 1,109 men and 315 women, for a total of 1,424 athletes, participated in these Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Fiji, Guam, Guatemala, Jamaica, the Netherlands Antilles and the Virgin Islands had their Winter Olympics debut in 1988.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There were 46 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, there were 22 events in 4 demonstration sports and disciplines that have no official status in the overall medal tally.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather conditions were a problem facing OCO'88 during the Games, with temperatures ranging from −28 to 22 °C (−18 to 72 °F).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After an unexpectedly freezing opening ceremony, the outdoor competitions scheduled to start the next day had to be postponed.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This ended up affecting the men's downhill skiing event at Nakiska which was postponed for one day, due to Chinook winds blowing up to 160 km/h.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The women's downhill event also experienced the same scenario.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] With the ski jumping venue facing north at Canada Olympic Park (COP), the same winds also disrupted those events, with the large hill event being postponed four times.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also disrupted the Nordic combined events, in which the ski jumping part had to be postponed as well.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This situation ended up causing something unprecedented in the history of the Winter Olympics, as for the first time both the ski jumping and Nordic combined cross-country skiing events were contested in a single day.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite using artificial cooling, the bobsleigh and luge events did not need to be rescheduled; however, several races had to be postponed because of the high temperatures recorded and also because of the dirt that was carried away by these winds.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA) Board of Directors had originally 25 members.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was chaired by Frank King, followed by former Mayors Ralph Klein and Ross Alger, and other prominent Calgarians.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The executive committee president was Robert Niven.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic Organizing Committee (OOC) was formed by utilizing many of the original board of directors members.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was initially started with 11 members and was grown to 25 members by October 1983.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It grew further to 29 members by 1985, when former Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, was added to the list.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] An Olympic biographer, Kevin Wamsley, noted that the CEO Frank King, President Bill Pratt, Ralph Klein, and former COA President Roger Jackson had collectively the most influence on all aspects of these Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This organizing committee took a hierarchical form for planning these Olympics, which caused consternation from some staff, volunteers, and people in executive roles.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The original staff, who were at odds with the current management structure, were either fired or willingly resigned.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, there were claims that some of the volunteers were verbally abused.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As a result, David Leighton resigned as OOC President in 1982, after only five months on the job.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Bill Pratt, a former general manager of the Calgary Stampede, became the new OCOG's president shortly afterwards.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The City of Calgary and the Canadian Olympic Association (COA) delegated officially all Olympic responsibilities, including staging the Winter Olympics under the Olympic Charter, to the newly formed OCO'88 in February and September 1983 respectively.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, conflicts within OCO'88 grew in the public eye and a review of the entire management structure was conducted after Ralph Klein threatened it with a public inquiry in 1986.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Thus, Frank King remained as CEO, but with the addition of more full-time staff.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, more than 9,000 volunteers were registered who were allocated to the most diverse areas.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite these changes, there was still some animosity within OCO'88.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Kevin Walmsley noted that Bill Pratt and Frank King continued to have a very tense relationship and that any movement caused sparks with each other.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games coincided with a shift in television policy by the International Olympic Committee and growing enthusiasm by broadcasters in the United States.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Amendments to the *Olympic Charter* in 1977 established a policy mandating joint television rights involving the IOC and the local organizing committee and was enshrined in the 1981 bid agreement for the Calgary games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The joint negotiating committee convened in 1984 late-January, some weeks before the Sarajevo 1984 Winter Games at the IOC's president residency at the Lausanne Palace were held to negotiate the Calgary television contracts with American broadcasters.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiating committee was represented by Dick Pound for the IOC, Bill Wardle for OCO'88 and consultant Barry Frank.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The co-negotiating committee designed a new tender process for the television rights bid with an emphasis on creating a level playing field for all broadcasters.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time, the negotiations were based on a series of sealed bids and representatives from ABC, CBS and NBC vied for the opportunity to broadcast the Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After six rounds of sealed bids, the ABC delegation led by producer Roone Arledge was successful with an agreement paying a record US$309 million (CA$386 million Canadian at the time) in exchange for exclusive rights for the games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CBS exited the bidding process after the second round with a final offer of $257 million, while ABC and NBC both reached the fifth round with an offer of $300 million.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the sixth and final stage, the IOC and OCO'88 decided a coin flip would determine which of ABC or NBC had the right to submit the first bid or defer, a decision neither network supported.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Watson elected to call the coin-flip, although he remained silent on the first flip, so a second coinflip was required, and NBC won with a choice of "heads", and after 30 minutes of deliberation submitted a $304 million bid.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's representative Arledge made a quick phone call to executive Fred Pierce, and ABC submitted a $309 million bid, exceeding NBC's bid by $5 million.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's record-setting bid was immediately controversial, first Arledge had exceeded the maximum allowable bid set by ABC's executives by $34 million, and in the coming weeks ABC's coverage of the 1984 Winter Olympics which cost $91.5 million returned poor Nielsen ratings.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Early estimates speculated the network would lose $50-$60 million televising the games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* described the NBC agreement as the "biggest prize of the Winter Olympics".
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The deal which was at the time the highest amount ever paid for a sporting event, allowed OCO'88 to announce the Games would be debt-free.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiations with American television broadcasters were in sharp contrast to negotiations for Western European rights with the European Broadcasting Union quickly closing an exclusive deal with the IOC for US$5.7 million led by Juan Antonio Samaranch and Marc Hodler on behalf of the IOC.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The *Calgary Herald* headline after the announcement negatively reflected on the "bargain" the European network received, and OCO'88 chairman Frank King publicly expressed his disappointment with the IOC.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Samaranch's argument for providing for a privileged negotiation with EBU was ensuring European viewers had equal access and coverage of the games, something he did not believe would occur if private networks from each nation were provided with the opportunity to bid.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dick Pound was also critical of the decision and argued more revenue could be brought in from BBC and RAI alone and the privileged status suppressed the willingness of the EBU to make a market-value bid on the games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CTV Television Network won the bid to broadcast the Games in Canada in December 1983, paying CA$4.5 million for the exclusive rights.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CTV also won the $23.5 million contract to serve as the host broadcaster, responsible for the manpower and equipment to televise the games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, while the bid was strengthened, CBC and CTV signed an agreement that if Calgary were the eventual winner, the two broadcasters would create a consortium in which the purchase of television rights would take place jointly.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The previous arrangement had CBC provide full coverage for Summer Games with CTV broadcasting a nightly summary, while CTV had the rights to Winter Games with CBC broadcasting a nightly summary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The nightly summary of the Games was also televised on CBC.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Japan's broadcast rights were awarded to NHK in July 1986 for US$3.9 million.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 made several alterations to the Olympic program as part of efforts to ensure value for its broadcast partners.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Now, the premier and main events, including ice hockey and figure skating, were scheduled for prime time and the Games were lengthened to 15 days from the previous 12 to ensure three weekends of coverage.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, a significant downturn in advertising revenue for sporting events resulted in ABC forecasting significant financial losses on the Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary organizers appreciated their fortunate timing in signing the deal.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King described the timing of the contract with ABC as "the passing of the sun and the moon at the right time for Calgary".
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The revenue growth from broadcasting was significant for the Calgary Games, OCO'88 generated $324.9 million in broadcast rights, which was a significant growth over an eight-period (the 1980 Lake Placid Games generated US$20.7 million).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC had net losses of more than $60 million, and broadcast rights to the 1992 Winter Olympics were later sold to the CBS network for $243 million, a 20 per cent reduction compared to Calgary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A series of ticket-related scandals plagued the organizing committee as the Games approached, resulting in widespread public anger.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Demand for tickets was high, particularly for the main events which had sold out a year in advance.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Residents had been promised that only 10 per cent of tickets would go to "Olympic insiders", IOC officials and sponsors, but OCO'88 was later forced to admit that up to 50 percent of seats to top events had gone to insiders.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The organizing committee, which was subsequently chastised by mayor Klein for running a "closed shop", admitted that it had failed to properly communicate the obligations it had to supply IOC officials and sponsors with priority tickets.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At that time, the American dollar was trading 40 cents higher than the Canadian dollar, resulting in significantly higher than anticipated revenue through currency conversion.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The ticket manager maintained his innocence claiming he was used as a scapegoat and sponsor credit card Visa was responsible for the error, despite his claims, the ticketing manager was convicted of fraud, theft, and forgery, and sentenced to 5 years in prison.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Organizers attempted to respond to public concern by asking sponsors to consider reducing their orders and by paying $1.5 million to add 2,600 seats to the Saddledome, as well as increase capacity for ski jumping, alpine skiing and the opening ceremonies.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This led to a change of the venue of the closing ceremonies from Saddledome to McMahon Stadium, as the stadium capacity was about two times bigger than the indoor venue.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King also noted that the Calgary Games offered a then-record 1.9 million tickets for sale, three times the amount available at Sarajevo or Lake Placid and that 79 percent of them were to be allocated to Calgarians.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] By the start of the 1988 Winter Games, a record of over 1.4 million tickets had been sold, a figure that eclipsed the previous three Winter Games combined.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the OCO'88's final report, the Committee admits the culmination of fraud charges, a large portion of premier tickets requested by Olympic insiders, and poor communications led to a negative public reaction to the ticketing process.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time in the history of the Olympics, both summer and winter, the Organizing Committee worked with a refund policy for returned or unused tickets.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When an event was postponed by at least 24 hours, the ticketholder was eligible for a refund.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Due to weather issues, the 8 events that were scheduled for the first 24 hours had to be rescheduled, resulting in 130,000 ticket refunds totalling CA$2.9 million, with transactions handled by the Royal Bank of Canada.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The city of Calgary is world-renowned for the enthusiasm of its population for volunteer work which is reflected in the annual Calgary Stampede, which also relied heavily on volunteers to run the Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Over 22,000 people signed up for more than 9,400 positions, no matter how inglorious: doctors, lawyers and executives even offered to collect the waste generated during the opening ceremony.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, for the first time, a "Homestay" program was created and several local families opened their homes to visitors from around the world, and others were renting their rooms or houses to those who could not stay in pay a reserve in a hotel.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Klein was among those who felt it necessary that the event be community driven, a decision which allowed the city's welcoming spirit to manifest.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games' mascots, Hidy and Howdy, were designed to evoke images of "western hospitality".
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The smiling, cowboy-themed polar bears were popular across Canada.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Played by a team of 150 students from Bishop Carroll High School, the sister-brother pair made up to 300 appearances per month in the lead-up to the Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From their introduction at the closing ceremonies of the Sarajevo Games in 1984 until their retirement at the conclusion of the Calgary Games, the pair made about 50,000 appearances.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The iconic mascots graced signs welcoming travellers to Calgary for nearly two decades until they were replaced in 2007.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The mascot's names "Hidy" and "Howdy" were chosen by a public contest.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games were the most expensive Games, summer or winter, to be held at that time, with total expenses exceeding CA$879.6 million.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The high cost was anticipated, as organizers were aware at the outset of their bid that most facilities would have to be constructed.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The venues, constructed primarily with public money, were designed to have lasting use beyond the Games and were planned to become the home of several of Canada's national winter sports teams.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The record-breaking cost of the Calgary Olympics came in stark contrast to the original projections during the 1981 bid, which estimated a total cost of CA$218 million, split between CA$126 million in capital costs and CA$92 million in operating costs.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The significant growth in capital expenditures came despite the three levels of government taking over projects which constituted nearly half of the original budgeted capital projects.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Of the total expenses for the Games (CA$879.6 million), the Government of Canada contributed CA$200 million (22.7 per cent), the Government of Alberta contributed CA$130 million (14.8 per cent), and the City of Calgary contributed CA$43 million (4.9 per cent).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CA$320.8 million of government capital contributions not directly included in OCO'88's revenue statements included the Government of Canada constructing the CA$72.2 million Canada Olympic Park, and CA$40 million for the Olympic Oval.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Provincial expenses included CA$14.4 million to build the Canmore Nordic Centre, and CA$25.3 million to build Nakiska.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All three governments contributed to the CA$97.7 million Olympic Saddledome.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were a major economic boom for the city, which had fallen into its worst recession in 40 years following the collapse of both oil and grain prices three years before the games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A report prepared for the city in January 1985 estimated the games would create 11,100 man-years of employment and generate CA$450 million in salaries and wages.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In its post-Games report, OCO'88 estimated the Olympics created CA$1.4 billion in economic benefits across Canada during the 1980s, 70 percent within Alberta, as a result of capital spending, increased tourism and new sporting opportunities created by the facilities.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Olympic torch relay began on November 15, 1987, when the torch was lit at Olympia and Greek runner Stelios Bisbas began what was called "the longest torch run in history".
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's, Newfoundland on the Atlantic Ocean two days later and over 88 days, travelled west across the then 10 Canadian provinces and two territories.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It passed through most major cities, north to the Arctic Ocean at Inuvik, Northwest Territories, then west to the Pacific Ocean at Victoria, British Columbia before returning east to Alberta, and finally Calgary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch covered a distance of 18,000 kilometres (11,000 mi), the greatest distance for a torch relay in Olympic history until the 2000 Sydney Games, and a sharp contrast to the 1976 Montreal Games when the relay covered only 775 kilometres (482 mi).
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The identity of the final torchbearer who would light the Olympic cauldron was one of the Organizing Committee's most closely guarded secrets.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's with Barbara Ann Scott and Ferd Hayward representing Canada's past Olympians and ended with Ken Read and Cathy Priestner carrying the torch into McMahon Stadium representing the nation's current Olympians.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The design of the Olympic Torch for the Calgary games was a reproduction of the main landmark building of the Calgary skyline, the Calgary Tower.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The National Research Council Canada developed the design for the Torch, the base of the torch is made of maple wood, the national tree of Canada, aluminum, and hardened steel, all 100% collected in Canadian territory.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch was designed to remain lit despite the extreme conditions of Canadian winters.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Torch had to be light enough for relay runners to carry comfortably, and the final design came in at 60 centimetres in length and 1.7 kilograms in weight.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The maple handle portion included laser-incised pictograms of the 10 official Olympic Winter sports, and lettering was engraved on the steel caldron portion.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch used a mixed type of three fuels (gasoline, kerosene and alcohol) to allow a continuous burn during the unpredictable Canadian winter.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Approximately 100 torches were manufactured for the Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Governor General Jeanne Sauvé opened the Games on behalf of Queen Elizabeth II as an estimated 1.5 billion people watched the ceremony.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather was a dominant story throughout much of the Games, as strong chinook winds that brought daily temperatures as high as 17 °C (63 °F) wreaked havoc on the schedules for outdoor events.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Events were delayed when winds were deemed unsafe for competitors and organizers used artificial snow making equipment to ensure skiing venues were properly prepared.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first time in Olympic history that alpine events were held on artificial snow.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were also marred by the death of the Austrian ski team's doctor, Joerg Oberhammer, on February 25 after a collision with another skier threw him underneath a working snow grooming machine at Nakiska, crushing and killing him instantly.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The top individual competitors at the Olympics were Finnish ski jumper Matti Nykänen and Dutch speed skater Yvonne van Gennip as they each won three gold medals.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Italy's Alberto Tomba won gold in two skiing events, his first of five career Olympic medals en route to becoming the first alpine skier to win medals at three Winter Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] East Germany's Katarina Witt defended her 1984 gold medal in women's figure skating, capturing a second gold in Calgary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Her compatriot Christa Rothenburger won the gold medal in the 1000 metre race in speed skating, then went on to win a silver medal in the team sprint cycling event at the 1988 Summer Games to become the only person in Olympic history to win medals at both Olympic Games in the same year.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won gold in ice hockey as Nordic neighbours Finland and Sweden took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As it had in 1976, Canada again failed to win an official gold medal as the host of an Olympic Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canadians won two gold medals in demonstration events, including by Sylvie Daigle as one of her five medals in short-track speed skating.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canada's top official performances came in figure skating where Brian Orser and Elizabeth Manley each won silver medals.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Boitano won the gold medal over Orser by one-tenth of a point.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Witt won the gold while Thomas won the bronze medal.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Manley was not viewed as a medal contender, but skated the greatest performance of her career to come within a fraction of Witt's gold medal-winning score.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] American speed skater Dan Jansen's personal tragedy was one of the more poignant events of the Games as he skated the 500 metre race mere hours after his sister Jane died of leukemia.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A gold medal favourite, Jansen chose to compete as he felt it is what his sister would have wanted.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Viewers around the world witnessed his heartbreak as he fell and crashed into the outer wall in the first quarter of his heat.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the 1000 metre race four days later, Jansen was on a world record pace when he again fell.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After failing again in Albertville, Jansen finally won a gold medal at the 1994 Lillehamer Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One of the most popular athletes from the games was British ski jumper Michael Edwards, who gained infamy by placing last in both the 70 and 90 metre events finishing 70 and 53 points behind his next closest competitor, respectively.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Edwards' "heroic failure" made him an instant celebrity; he went from earning £6,000 per year as a plasterer before the Games to making £10,000 per hour per appearance afterward.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Left embarrassed by the spectacle he created, the IOC altered the rules following Calgary to eliminate each nation's right to send at least one athlete and set minimum competition standards for future events.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Regardless, the President of the Organizing Committee, Frank King, playfully saluted Edwards' unorthodox sporting legacy, which would also be commemorated with a 2016 feature film, *Eddie the Eagle*.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Jamaican bobsleigh team, making their nation's Winter Olympic debut, was also popular in Calgary.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The team was the brainchild of a pair of Americans who recruited individuals with strong sprinting ability from the Jamaican military to form the team.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dudley Stokes and Michael White finished the two-man event in 30th place out of 41 competitors and launched the Jamaican team into worldwide fame.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The pair, along with Devon Harris and Chris Stokes, crashed in the four-man event, but were met with cheers from the crowd as they pushed their sled across the finish line.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Their odyssey was made into the 1993 movie *Cool Runnings*, a largely fictionalized comedy by Walt Disney Pictures.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All of the long track world (WR) and Olympic records (OR) that occurred during these Games were later broken at succeeding Winter Olympics and other world events.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Prior to 1988, the Winter Olympics were viewed as a second-rate event, in comparison to the Summer Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The IOC had, at one point, considered eliminating it altogether.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] First, there are only a few mountainous areas in the world that would be able to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Second, there were major challenges in generating revenues for the host city and the IOC from such Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, CODA convinced the IOC that it could not only generate enough revenues to make a profit but have enough money left over to ensure a lasting legacy of winter sports development.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] OCO'88 followed mainly the example of LAOOC which organized the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Under LAOOC's president, Peter Ueberroth, he was able to attract a large United States television contract and Los Angeles became the first Olympic host city to make a profit.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 1988 Winter Olympics, OCO'88 attracted financial support from over two dozen major Canadian and multinational corporations, in order to generate millions of dollars in revenues.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For OCO'88, it foresaw some winter sports, like the debut of the Super-G and other new winter sports events, as a way to increase the audience's appeal of the Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Thus, for the sponsors, the Games' length of time to 15 days provided an extra weekend of Olympic media coverage to the world.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This additional programming time was filled mainly by TV-friendly demonstration events that are popular in Canada.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The 1988 Winter Olympics' exposure to curling, freestyle skiing, and short track speed skating events in Calgary influenced the worldwide popularity of all of them.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] So much so that all these events became the new and official Olympic finals in the period between the 1992 Winter Olympics to the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Hosting the Winter Olympics helped fuel a significant increase in Calgary's reputation on the world stage.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Crosbie Cotton, a reporter for the *Calgary Herald* who covered the city's Olympic odyssey from its 1979 initiative to the closing ceremonies, noted an increased positive outlook of the city's population over time.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] He believed that the populace began to outgrow its "giant inferiority complex" that is "typically Canadian", by replacing it with a new level of confidence as the Games approached.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This outcome helped the city grow from a regional oil and gas centre, best known for the Calgary Stampede, to a destination for international political, economic, and sporting events.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] A study prepared for the organizing committee of the 2010 Winter Olympics, (VANOC), claimed that Calgary hosted over 200 national and international sporting competitions between 1987 and 2007, due to the facilities it had constructed for these Olympic Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The Games' enduring popularity within Calgary has been attributed to efforts in making them "everybody's Games." Aside from the sense of community fostered by the high level of volunteer support, OCO'88 included the general public in other ways.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For example, the citizens were given an opportunity to purchase a brick with their names engraved on it.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Those bricks were used to build the Olympic Plaza, where the medal ceremonies were held in 1988.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It remains a popular public park and event site in the city's downtown core today.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After the success of these Olympic Games, Calgary was wanting to bring back the Olympic experience again.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It offered, to the IOC, in becoming a possible alternate host city of the 2002 Winter Olympics, after a bidding scandal resulted in speculation that Salt Lake City would not be able to remain the host city.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Next, the city was attempting to be Canada's bid for the 2010 Winter Olympics, but the COC decided to give it to Vancouver and Whistler.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Later, a 2013 *Calgary Sun* online poll found that 81% of respondents said they would support the idea of hosting another Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 13, 2018, Calgary held a public non-binding plebiscite on whether it should bid to host the 2026 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 19, 2018, the results of the plebiscite showed that 56.4% (171,750) of eligible voters said "No", while 43.6% (132,832) of them said "Yes." Therefore, the city council concluded that the bid would be withdrawn.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] In light of the 1976 Summer Olympics' disastrous financial legacy, the Calgary Olympic organizing committee, OCO'88, parlayed its ability to generate television and sponsorship revenues, along with the three levels of government support, into what was ultimately a C$170 million surplus.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] While OCO'88 reported officially a surplus after the Games were over, the accounting practices of the final report did not include federal, provincial, and municipal capital and operations funding infrastructures.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The overall surplus was turned into endowment funds that were split between Canada Olympic Park (C$110 million) and CODA.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] They were subsequently reformed later, in order to manage the Olympic facilities with a trust fund that had grown steadily to be worth over C$200 million by 2013.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Consequently, all five primary facilities built for the 1988 Winter Olympics remained operational for their intended purposes, 25 years after the Games concluded.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Calgary and Canmore became the heart of winter sports in Canada, as CODA (now known as WinSport) established itself as the nation's leader in developing elite winter athletes.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 2006 Winter Olympics, a quarter of Canada's Olympic winter athletes were from the Calgary region and three-quarters of its medalists were from or trained in Alberta.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Before 1988, Canada was not a winter sports power.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The nation's five overall medals won in Calgary was its second-best total at a Winter Olympics, behind the seven overall medals it won at the 1932 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid, New York.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After 1988, Canada won an increasing number of gold and overall medals at each successive Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It culminated in an overall performance of 26 medals won at the 2010 Winter Olympics, which included the previous Olympic record of 14 gold medals.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Until 2010, Norway won the most Olympic gold medals on home soil at the 1952 Winter Olympics.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, Norway recaptured the record of winning the most Olympic gold medals at a single Winter Olympics in 2022, claiming 16.
[src:canada/1988-winter-olympics-p02] At the 2018 Winter Olympics, Canada earned its highest overall medal count in the Winter Olympics to date, with a total of 29 medals.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The **1995 Quebec referendum** was the second referendum to ask voters in the predominantly French-speaking Canadian province of Quebec whether Quebec should proclaim sovereignty and become an independent country, with the condition precedent of offering a political and economic agreement to Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The culmination of multiple years of debate and planning after the failure of the Meech Lake and Charlottetown constitutional accords, the referendum was launched by the provincial Parti Québécois government of Jacques Parizeau.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Despite initial predictions of a heavy sovereignist defeat, an eventful and complex campaign followed, with the "Yes" side flourishing after being taken over by Bloc Québécois leader Lucien Bouchard.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Voting took place on 30 October 1995, and featured the largest voter turnout in Quebec's history (93.52%).
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The "No" option carried by a margin of 54,288 votes, receiving 50.58% of the votes cast.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Controversies over both the provincial vote counting and direct federal financial involvement in the final days of the campaign reverberated in Canadian politics for over a decade after the referendum took place.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Quebec, a province in Canada since its foundation in 1867, has always been the sole majority French-speaking province.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Among these was René Lévesque, who founded the Parti Québécois with like-minded groups seeking independence from Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] After winning power in 1976, the PQ government held a referendum in 1980 seeking a mandate to negotiate "sovereignty-association" with Canada, which was decisively defeated.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In response to the referendum result, Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau said that he would seek to patriate the Canadian Constitution and institute what would eventually become the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] During tense negotiations in November 1981, an agreement was reached between Trudeau and nine of the ten provincial premiers by Trudeau, but not Lévesque.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Constitution Act 1982 was enacted without the Quebec National Assembly's approval, after the Supreme Court of Canada ruled against the Quebec government that its consent was not necessary for constitutional change.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] New Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and Quebec Liberal premier Robert Bourassa sought a series of constitutional amendments designed to address Quebec's concerns.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In the Meech Lake Accord, the federal government and all provincial premiers agreed to a series of amendments that decentralized some powers and recognized Quebec as a distinct society.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Accord, after fierce debate in English Canada, fell apart in dramatic fashion in the summer of 1990, as two provinces failed to ratify it within the three-year time limit required by the constitution.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] This prompted outrage among Quebec nationalists and a surge in support for sovereignty.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] While the Accord was collapsing, Lucien Bouchard, a cabinet minister in Mulroney's government, led a coalition of six Progressive Conservative members of parliament and one Liberal MP from Quebec to form a new federal party devoted to Quebec sovereignty, the Bloc Québécois.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Following these events, Bourassa said that a referendum would be held in 1992, with either sovereignty or a new constitutional agreement as the subject.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] This prompted a national referendum on the Charlottetown Accord of 1992, a series of constitutional amendments that included the proposals of the Meech Lake Accord as well as other matters.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Accord was rejected by a majority of voters both in Quebec and English Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In the 1993 federal election, the Liberals returned to power with a majority government under Jean Chrétien, who had been Minister of Justice during the 1980–81 constitutional discussions and the Bloc Québécois won 54 seats with 49.3% of Quebec's vote.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The result made the Bloc the second largest party in the House of Commons, giving it the role of Official Opposition and allowing Bouchard to confront Chrétien in Question Period on a daily basis.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In Quebec, the 1994 provincial election brought the Parti Québécois back to power, led by Jacques Parizeau.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The party's platform promised to hold a referendum on sovereignty during the first year of its term in office.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The PQ won a majority government with 44.75% of the popular vote, just ahead of the Liberals' 44.4%.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In preparation for the referendum, every household in Quebec was sent a draft of the *Act Respecting the Future of Quebec* (also referred to as the *Sovereignty Bill*), with the announcement of the National Commission on the Future of Quebec to commence in February 1995.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The commission was boycotted by the Liberal Party of Quebec, the Liberal Party of Canada, and the Progressive Conservative Party of Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The primary issue of debate within the sovereignty movement became on what terms sovereignty would be put before the electorate.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] As a practical matter, Parizeau believed that given the emotional circumstances of separation a special partnership was unlikely, and that given free trade agreements and other multilateral institutions it was unnecessary.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau's stance created opposition in the sovereignty movement, which coalesced around Bloc Québécois leader Lucien Bouchard.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] A popular and charismatic figure, Bouchard had come close to death from necrotizing fasciitis and lost his left leg.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] His recovery, and subsequent public appearances on crutches, provided a rallying point for sovereigntists and the public at large.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard thought a proposal lacking a partnership would doom the project among soft nationalists (such as himself) who worried about the economic consequences of separation.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] As polls showed Parizeau's approach as highly unlikely to even exceed 40% support in a referendum, leaders of the movement engaged in a heated public debate.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Mario Dumont, leader of the new Action démocratique du Québec, also stated that he would only consider participation in the referendum if a partnership was made part of the question.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The final findings of the National Commission, issued April 19, included a statement that the public generally desired an economic partnership with Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Fearing Bouchard and Dumont would further dilute their position as the referendum wore on, Parizeau agreed to negotiate a broader approach, and would agree to a statement that included partnership with Dumont and Bouchard on June 12, 1995.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Agreement contained details of the partnership negotiation process, and a general plan of seeking "sovereignty" while requiring an economic and social partnership offer be negotiated and presented to the rest of Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Most importantly for Parizeau, the agreement also allowed the government to declare immediate independence if negotiations were not successful or heard after a successful referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The looming referendum prompted a number of actions in the Quebec Superior Court, which were consolidated under the application of prominent lawyer Guy Bertrand.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bertrand asked for interim and permanent injunctions against the holding of the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Federal Attorney General declined to intervene, and after failing in a motion to strike the application, the Quebec Attorney General unilaterally withdrew from the hearing.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Quebec government moved the September sitting of the National Assembly two days forward to be sure that parliamentary immunity would prevent MNAs from being summoned to testify.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Court opted for declaratory relief, declaring that the *Sovereignty Bill* and the referendum constituted a serious threat to Bertrand's Charter rights.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau denounced the decision as undemocratic, stated that the *Constitution Act, 1982* did not apply to Quebec, and refused to move the referendum timetable.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Quebec Attorney General Paul Bégin stated that he believed an extra-constitutional referendum was legal pursuant to international law.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Quebec Liberal leader and "No" campaign chairman Daniel Johnson announced the following day that the ruling would not change the strategy of the "No" campaign.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Some Federal officials questioned if their level of government could be involved after the declaration, but ultimately the Federal government decided to participate.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In a dramatic reading at the Grand Théâtre de Québec on September 6, the final version of the *Sovereignty Bill* was unveiled.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The bill would be tabled in the National Assembly awaiting the result of the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The question in the 1980 referendum, in an attempt to build a broad coalition, had sought only the authority to negotiate sovereignty with the Canadian government, and promised a second referendum to ratify the results of any negotiation.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau believed a second referendum was unnecessary and would only encourage the remainder of Canada to use delaying tactics.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The draft initial act featured a question only asking for the authority to declare Quebec sovereign.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Pursuant to the partnership agreement with Bouchard and Dumont, the referendum question was changed to incorporate the partnership agreement.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] It was presented on September 7, 1995, to be voted on October 30, 1995.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The question came under immediate fire from federalists, who had no input in the drafting.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Other federalists argued that the question erroneously implied an agreement had been reached between Canada and Quebec regarding a partnership on June 12, 1995.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau would later express regret that the agreement had to be cited in the question, but noted that the June 12, 1995 agreement had been sent to every registered voter in the province.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Each committee had an authorized budget of $5 million.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Campaign spending by any person or group other than the official committees would be illegal after the official beginning of the referendum campaign.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] After the agreement of June 12, the "Yes" campaign would be headed by Jacques Parizeau.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The official "No" campaign would be chaired by Liberal leader Daniel Johnson Jr.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Making matters more complex, especially for the "No" camp, was the federal nature of Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The governing Liberal Party of Canada and its leader, Prime Minister Jean Chrétien were not strongly represented in the province outside of Montreal.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Chrétien's involvement in the 1982 negotiations and his stance against the Meech Lake Accord made him unpopular with moderate francophone federalists and sovereignists, who would be the swing voters in the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Lucienne Robillard, a nationalist former Bourassa-era cabinet minister, would serve as the federal Liberal representative on the "No" committee.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Jean Charest, leader of the Federal Progressive Conservative Party, would be prominently featured, as he and the PCs had closely and productively cooperated with the Quebec Liberals in the Meech Lake negotiations.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Fearing missteps by politicians not used to Quebec that had occurred during the Meech Lake and Charlottetown debates, Johnson and the campaign heavily controlled appearances by Federal politicians, including Chrétien.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Johnson bluntly banned any appearance by the Reform Party or its leader, Preston Manning.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] This would go unchallenged by Ottawa for the majority of the campaign, but created much frustration within the governing Liberals in Ottawa.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Prominent Chrétien adviser Eddie Goldenberg believed that the "No" campaign at some points was more focused on the future election position of the Quebec Liberals rather than the referendum itself.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The campaign officially began on October 2, 1995, with a televised address by both leaders.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau emphasized that he believed this might be the last opportunity for sovereignty for the foreseeable future, while Johnson chose to forecast the uncertainty that a "Yes" vote could provoke.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Johnson's campaign focused on the practical problems created by the sovereignty process, emphasizing that an independent Quebec would be in an uncertain position regarding the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and not be able to control the Canadian dollar.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Prominent business figures such as Power Corporation president Paul Desmarais and Bombardier Inc. head Laurent Beaudoin spoke that they believed a "Yes" victory could spell doom for their Quebec business interests.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The initial campaign for the "Yes" was led by Parizeau, with Dumont campaigning separately in rural areas.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In addition to the traditional themes of the movement's appeal to Quebec nationalism, the "Yes" campaign attempted to highlight the slim possibility of any future reform to Canada's federal system.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau bitterly attacked business leaders for intervening in the referendum, calling it a betrayal of their Quebec customers and workers.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] While Parizeau's responses were highly popular with "Yes" stalwarts, it was generally seen that speeches against business leaders were only highlighting the economic uncertainty that worried swing voters.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Polls in the first week were highly disappointing for the "Yes" camp, as they showed them behind by 5–7 percentage points among decided voters, with an even larger gap if "undecided" voters were weighed toward the "No" side as would generally be expected.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau, a general fixture in Quebec politics for decades whose strong views of sovereignty were well known among the populace, was under pressure to create a spark.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In an unannounced ceremony on October 7 at the Université de Montréal, Parizeau made a surprise announcement: He appointed Bouchard as "chief negotiator" for the partnership talks following a "Yes" vote.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The move came as a dramatic surprise to the campaign, promoting the popular Bouchard to the fore and simultaneously emphasizing the "partnership" aspect of the question.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard, already popular, became a sensation: in addition to his medical struggles and charisma, his more moderate approach and prominent involvement in the Meech Lake Accord while in Ottawa reminded undecided nationalist voters of federal missteps from years past.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Politicians on both sides described his appeal as messianic and almost impossible to personally attack, in contrast to the well-worn figures on both sides of the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] "No" advisor John Parisella noted that at focus groups, when presented with statements Bouchard had made that they did not like, participants would refuse to believe he meant them.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] New polls eventually showed a majority of Quebecers intending to vote "Yes".
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] "No" forces, including Johnson, were shocked by the development, which required wholesale changes in strategy three weeks before the vote.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Unwilling to believe Parizeau had given up his leadership role voluntarily, most in the "No" camp and Ottawa had assumed a coup had taken place, though the manoeuvre had been planned and voluntary.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The dramatic events prompted many federal politicians to lobby for similarly dramatic intervention from Ottawa and the federal government, which were refused by the "No" committee, who believed that with Bouchard's introduction the margin for error was dramatically reduced.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The "No" campaign continued to focus on the economic benefits of federation.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard's speeches asked Quebecers to vote "Yes" to give a clear mandate for change, and that only the clarity of a "Yes" vote would provide a final solution to Canada's long-standing constitutional issues and a new partnership with English Canada for the betterment of both.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard's popularity was such that his remarks that the Québécois were the "white race" with the lowest rate of reproduction, which threatened to cast the project as focused on ethnic nationalism, were traversed with ease.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Pursuant to the *Referendum Act*, both committees were required to contribute to a brochure sent to every voter describing their positions.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The official "No" brochure, written by the Quebec Liberals, stated that Quebec was a distinct society, and that Quebec should enjoy full autonomy in areas of provincial jurisdiction.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Parizeau, while speaking in Hull, challenged Chrétien to tell voters that, if "No" won, Ottawa would withdraw from all provincial jurisdictions, prompting a vague response from the "No" campaign.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] On October 21 in Longueuil, Johnson, hoping to defuse the issue, ad-libbed a challenge to Chrétien to declare his position on distinct society recognition.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] When presented with the request, Chrétien, in New York for a United Nations meeting, responded, "No.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] We're not talking about the Constitution, we're talking about the separation of Quebec from the rest of Canada." The remarks in direct contradiction to Johnson were portrayed in the press as a blunt refusal.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Chrétien's position was far more difficult than Johnson's: part of the 1993 Liberal election platform had been moving the country away from large-scale constitutional debates.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Provincial governments were also far more hostile to the constitutional process than they had been in the decade prior, with even the federal government's typical ally, Ontario, being firmly against any pursuit of constitutional accommodation.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] French President Jacques Chirac, while answering a call from a viewer in Montreal on CNN's *Larry King Live*, said that, if the "Yes" side were successful, the fact that the referendum had succeeded would be recognized by France.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The sudden reversal of Chrétien's long-standing position on the issue, along with Chrétien's wan complexion and atypically nervous appearance, sparked considerable comment.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Charest further emphasized his commitment to constitutional reform if a "No" victory was achieved.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] In response to the referendum, Indigenous peoples in Quebec strongly affirmed their own right to self-determination.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] First Nations chiefs said that forcing their peoples to join an independent Quebec without their consent would violate international law, violating their rights to self-determination.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Indigenous groups also demanded to be full participants in any new constitutional negotiations resulting from the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] First Nations communities contributed significantly to the tense debate on a hypothetical partition of Quebec.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Grand Council of the Crees in Northern Quebec was particularly vocal and prominent in its resistance to the idea of being included in an independent Quebec.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Grand Chief Matthew Coon Come issued a legal paper, titled *Sovereign Injustice*, which sought to affirm the Cree right to self-determination in keeping their territories in Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Inuit of Nunavik held a similar local vote, asking voters, ***"Do you agree that Quebec should become sovereign?"***, with 96% voting No.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Blanchard, the U.S. ambassador to Canada in 1993–1996, secretly opposed Quebec's separatist movement.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Blanchard engineered a last-minute statement supporting a united Canada by President Bill Clinton.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The same night, Prime Minister Jean Chrétien gave a televised address to the nation in English and French.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The "Yes" side was provided airtime for a rebuttal in English and French.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Lucien Bouchard was given the task in both languages, with the "Yes" campaign stating that a federal politician should give the response.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard's French address recounted the previous animosities of the constitutional debate, specifically targeting Chrétien's career and actions, including showing a newspaper headline from the aftermath of the 1982 Constitution that featured Trudeau and Chrétien laughing.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard then focused on the details of the partnership aspect of the proposal.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] He used his English address to ask Canadians to understand the "Yes" side and to announce an intention to negotiate in good faith.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The next day, Montreal radio station CKOI broadcast a prank call by radio announcer Pierre Brassard, impersonating Chrétien, to Elizabeth II, Queen of Canada, asking her to make a televised address championing national unity.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The Queen appeared to reluctantly agree to the request and talked to Brassard for 17 minutes before her staff identified the hoax (after a delay due to a Chrétien aide wrongly speculating to Buckingham Palace staff that it could be a genuine call).
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Fisheries Minister Brian Tobin, expressing anxiety to his staff about the referendum the week before, was told about a small rally planned in Place du Canada in Montreal for businesspersons on October 27.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Asked by Federal advisor John Rae, Pierre Claude Nolin agreed to allow Tobin to invite Canadians outside Quebec to the rally, provided Quebec's referendum laws were adhered to.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Tobin then encouraged fellow caucus members to send as many people as possible.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Tobin proceeded to call the chairman of Air Canada in his capacity as a private citizen and suggest planes be made available at the same rate, a request that was granted.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Tobin's Canada AM appearance resulted in calls flooding MP's offices in English Canada, and bus companies volunteered hundreds of vehicles to take Canadians from outside of Quebec to Montreal.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The rally at Place du Canada was estimated to have between 50,000 and 125,000 attendees, with estimates varying wildly as the crowd grew and shrank throughout the day.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Jean Chrétien, Jean Charest and Daniel Johnson spoke to the crowd for the occasion, which would become known as the "Unity Rally".
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Images of the large crowd with an oversized Canadian flag became iconic.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Charest felt the rally helped to keep momentum for the "No" campaign moving.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The federal government's intervention in the rally attracted strident protests from the "Yes" side, who felt the discounts and coordination were an illegal intervention in the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bouchard publicly contrasted the rally with what he believed was the inattention of English Canada to the collapse of the Meech Lake Accord.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Nolin regretted granting permission for the "No" committee once the scale became known, and Johnson felt the rally only exacerbated tensions with regard to English Canada.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Opinions on whether the rally had an impact were divided and unable to be gauged, as the rally happened while the final polls for the Monday referendum were being produced.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] During the campaign, polls were reported by all pollsters and press outlets with a general guideline of having undecided voters split unevenly in favour of the "No" side: This ranged from 2/3 to 3/4 of the undecided vote.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] 93.52% of the 5,087,009 registered Quebecers voted in the referendum, a higher turnout than any provincial or federal election in Canada's history.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The proposal of June 12, 1995 was rejected by voters, with 50.58% voting "No" and 49.42% voting "Yes".
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The margin was significantly smaller than the 1980 referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The "Yes" side was the choice of French speakers by an estimated majority of about 60%.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Anglophones and allophones (those who do not have English or French as a first language) voted "No" by a margin of 95%.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] There was a majority "Yes" vote in 80 out of 125 National Assembly ridings.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The "Yes" side was strongest in Saguenay–Lac-Saint-Jean, the Gaspé, the Centre-du-Québec, and generally the suburbs of Quebec City and Montreal.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] While there was disappointment in the results of Montreal and the Beauce, Quebec City's soft support for "Yes" was the greatest surprise for the "Yes" side.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] This prompted speculation that provincial civil servants did not want the uncertainty a "Yes" would bring, especially after Parizeau had promised to integrate displaced Federal civil servants in a sovereign Quebec.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The largest support for the "No" vote was found in Montreal, the province's largest city; ridings in the West Island, home to a large anglophone population, voted "No" by margins eclipsing 80%, with some polling stations recording no "Yes" votes at all.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The far North, the Outaouais, the Beauce, and the Eastern Townships also generally voted "No".
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] "No" supporters gathered at Métropolis in Montreal, where Johnson expressed hope for reconciliation in Quebec and stated he expected the federal government to pursue constitutional changes.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Prime Minister Chrétien echoed similar sentiments to Johnson, and stated that he "extended his hand" to Quebec's premier and government.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] "Yes" supporters met at the Palais des congrès de Montréal on referendum night.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] After the result became known, Dumont and Bouchard made speeches accepting the result as part of the movement's democratic convictions and expressing hope that a subsequent referendum would bring a "Yes" victory.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Jacques Parizeau, who had not prepared a concession speech, rejected one prepared by Jean-François Lisée and spoke without notes.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] The remarks, widely lambasted in the Canadian and international press as ethnocentric, sparked surprise and anger in the "Yes" camp, as the movement had gone to great lengths to disown ethnic nationalism.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Bernard Landry confronted Parizeau at a Cabinet meeting the next morning about the remarks, stating that the movement "had to hide its head in shame." Parizeau, after canvassing opinions, then told his Cabinet that he would resign as premier and leader of the Parti Québécois.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] It was later revealed that he had declared he would retire anyway if the "Yes" side lost, in an embargoed interview with TVA taped days before the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Six days after the referendum, André Dallaire, a "Yes" supporter with schizophrenia, upset at the result, broke into Chrétien's Ottawa residence armed with a knife.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Dallaire attempted to find Chrétien and kill the prime minister in his bed before being discovered by Aline Chrétien, who barricaded the bedroom door.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p01] Chrétien was unharmed, and Dallaire was eventually found not criminally responsible by reason of mental defect.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Sovereignists believed that a "Yes" vote of 50% plus one vote was a binding result pursuant to the *Referendum Act* and the *Sovereignty Bill*, as well as the general international law principle of self-determination.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] In the event of a "Yes" victory, Parizeau had said he intended to return to the National Assembly of Quebec within two days of the result and seek support for a motion recognizing the result of the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] In a speech he had prepared in the event of a "Yes" victory, he said a sovereign Quebec's first move would be to "extend a hand to its Canadian neighbour" in partnership pursuant to the wording of the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Despite the prominent placement of Bouchard in the referendum campaign, Parizeau planned to retain all authority with regard to negotiations, and to appoint most members of the negotiation team if they were to occur.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Parizeau also believed federalist Quebecers such as Chrétien and Charest would be quickly disregarded and replaced at negotiations by representatives from the other nine provinces.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] If the Federal government refused to negotiate, or if negotiations were to exceed October 30, 1996, Parizeau stated that he would proceed with a unilateral declaration of independence (UDI) for an independent Quebec pursuant to Section 26 of the *Sovereignty Bill*.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Parizeau's hopes for international recognition, a practical requirement of statehood, rested with France and the Francophonie.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] He believed that if Quebec declared independence in these circumstances, President of the French National Assembly Philippe Séguin, a powerful Gaullist power broker who was sympathetic to the sovereignty movement, would pressure President Chirac to recognize the declaration.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] He counted on a French recognition to spread quickly to the Francophonie and bring the issue to a head.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Benoit Bouchard, Canada's ambassador at the time, believed that the plan was irrational as he doubted Séguin, who was supposed to be a neutral figure in his role, could bring sufficient pressure in the country's semi-presidential system.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] In interviews conducted in 2014, Bouchard and Dumont both believed that negotiations would have resulted had the "Yes" side won and that Quebec would have remained in Canada with a more autonomous status.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Bouchard, while approving of Parizeau's intention to unilaterally declare independence should negotiations be refused, implied that he and Dumont would have been able to control negotiations and offer a subsequent referendum on a new agreement.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Dumont noted that international recognition would have been difficult had two of the three leaders of the "Yes" campaign been against a UDI, and that he and Bouchard were willing to slow the process down if necessary.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] For his part, Bernard Landry believed that nothing short of a seat at the United Nations would have been accomplished had the "Yes" won.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] As the referendum was only of force and effect pursuant to a provincial law, neither the provincially sanctioned "No" committee nor the Federal government had any input on the question of the referendum.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Federalists strongly differed on how or if a "Yes" referendum result would be recognized.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] "No" campaign head Daniel Johnson disputed the "Yes" side's position that a simple majority was sufficient to declare independence, as he believed the question was too vague and gave negotiators too broad a mandate given the enormity of the issue and the uncertainty of negotiations.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Jean Chrétien refused to publicly comment or consider contingencies regarding a possible "Yes" victory, and at no point stated the referendum bound the Federal government to negotiations or permitted a unilateral declaration of independence.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] His wording of speeches during the referendum noted that Parizeau would interpret a "Yes" vote as a mandate to separate Quebec from Canada, but never offered recognition that this was legal or recognizable.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] A speech drafted for Chrétien in the event of a "Yes" vote stated that the question was too ambiguous to be binding and that only dissatisfaction with the status quo had been stated.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Reform party leader Preston Manning, a prominent proponent of direct democracy, would have recognized any result, with critics suspecting he preferred a "Yes" vote for electoral gain.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Jean Charest recognized the referendum's legitimacy, although a draft post-referendum speech had him interpreting a "Yes" vote as a call for drastic reform of Canadian federation instead of separation.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The New Democratic Party's official position was that the result had to be recognized.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Little planning was made for the possibility of a "Yes" vote by the Canadian federal government, with the general consensus being that the referendum would be easily won and that planning would spark panic or give the referendum undeserved legitimacy.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Some members of the federal cabinet met to discuss several possible scenarios, including referring the issue of Quebec's independence to the Supreme Court.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Senior civil servants met to consider the impact of a vote for secession on issues such as territorial boundaries and the federal debt.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] A dispute arose as to whether Jean Chrétien and many prominent members of Cabinet who had been elected in Quebec ridings could represent Canada at a hypothetical partnership negotiation.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Manning intended to immediately call for Chrétien's resignation and for a general election if the referendum were successful, even though the Liberals, independently of their Quebec seats, had a sizable majority in the House of Commons.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] There was also some doubt that Chrétien would be able to assure the governor general that he retained enough support within his party to remain the prime minister.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Chrétien's intention was, whatever the result, to stay in office.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] New Brunswick Premier Frank McKenna later confirmed that he had been invited into a hypothetical "national unity" cabinet if the "Yes" side was victorious, with a general understanding that former Ontario Premier Bob Rae was to be included as well.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Premier of Saskatchewan Roy Romanow secretly formed a committee to study consequences if Quebec successfully seceded, including strengthening Saskatchewan's relationships with other western provinces, also seceding from Canada, or joining the United States.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] When the counting was completed, approximately 86,000 ballots were rejected by Deputy Returning Officers, alleging that they had not been marked properly by the voter.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Each polling station featured a Deputy Returning Officer (appointed by the "Yes") who counted the ballots while a Poll Clerk (appointed by the "No") recorded the result of the count.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Controversy arose over whether the Deputy Returning Officers of the Chomedey, Marguerite-Bourgeois and Laurier-Dorion ridings had improperly rejected ballots.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] In these ridings the "No" vote was dominant, and the proportion of rejected ballots was 12%, 5.5% and 3.6%.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Thomas Mulcair, member of the Quebec National Assembly for Chomedey, told reporters that there was "an orchestrated attempt to steal the vote" in his riding.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] A study released months after the referendum by McGill University concluded that ridings with a greater number of "No" votes had a higher percentage of rejected ballots.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Directeur général des élections du Québec (DGEQ), Pierre F.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Cote, launched an inquiry into the alleged irregularities, supervised by the Chief Justice of the Quebec Superior Court, Alan B.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] All ballots of the three ridings plus a sample of ballots from other ridings were examined.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The inquiry concluded that some ballots had been rejected without valid reasons, but the incidents were isolated.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The majority of the rejected ballots were "No" votes, in proportion to the majority of the valid votes in those districts.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] A Quebec Court judge acquitted a Deputy Returning Officer charged with illegally rejecting 53% of the ballots cast at his Chomedey polling district.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] In 2000, the Quebec Superior Court denied an application by Alliance Quebec that attempted to force the DGEQ to give access to all 5 million ballots, ruling that the only authority that could do so expired in 1996.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The referendum ballots were shredded and recycled in 2008 after appeals were exhausted.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] In May 2005, former PQ Cabinet minister Richard Le Hir said that the PQ coordinated the ballot rejections, which PQ officials denied.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Citizenship Court judges from across Canada were sent into the province to ensure as many qualified immigrants living in Quebec as possible had Canadian citizenship before the referendum, and thus were able to vote.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The goal was to have 10,000 to 20,000 outstanding citizenship applications processed for residents of Quebec by mid-October.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] 43,855 new Quebecers obtained their Canadian citizenship during 1995, with about one quarter of these (11,429) being granted during the month of October.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Marchi would later admit that citizenship applications were hurried on Chrétien's direct orders to sway the vote to the "No" side.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The Canadian Unity Council incorporated a Montreal-based lobbying group called Option Canada with the mandate to promote federalism in Quebec.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Option Canada received $1.6 million in funding from the Canadian Heritage Department in 1994, $3.35 million in 1995 and $1.1 million in 1996.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The Montreal Gazette reported in March 1997 that the group also had other funds from undeclared sources.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] A Committee to Register Voters Outside Quebec was created to help citizens who had left Quebec before the 1995 vote register on the electoral list.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The Committee handed out pamphlets during the referendum, including a form to be added to the list of voters.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The pamphlet gave out a toll-free number as contact information, which was the same number as the one used by the Canadian Unity Council.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] After the referendum, the DSEQ filed 20 criminal charges of illegal expenditures by Option Canada and others on behalf of the "No" side, which were dropped after the Supreme Court of Canada in *Libman vs.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Quebec-Attorney General* ruled sections of the *Referendum Act* restricting third-party expenditures were unconstitutionally restrictive under the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Aurèle Gervais, communications director for the Liberal Party of Canada, as well as the students' association at Ottawa's Algonquin College, were charged with infractions of Quebec's Election Act after the referendum for illegally hiring buses to bring supporters to Montreal for the rally.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Environment Minister Sergio Marchi told reporters that Gervais should wear [the charges against him] like a badge of honour." Two years later, the Quebec Superior Court dismissed the charges, stating that the actions took place outside of Quebec and so the Quebec Election Act did not apply.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The DSEQ asked retired Quebec court judge Bernard Grenier in 2006 to investigate Option Canada after the publication of Normand Lester and Robin Philpot's "The Secrets of Option Canada", which alleged over $5,000,000 had been spent helping the "No" campaign.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Grenier determined that CA$539,000 was illegally spent by the "No" side during the referendum, although he drew no conclusions over the "Unity Rally." Grenier said there was no evidence of wrongdoing by Jean Charest or that the rally was part of a plan to sabotage the sovereigntist movement.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Grenier urged Quebecers in his report to move on.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The Bloc Québécois called for a federal inquiry, which did not occur.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] After the referendum, the ballot for Quebec elections was redesigned to reduce the size of the space where voters could indicate their choice and the rules on allowable markings were relaxed, so that Deputy Returning Officers would have fewer grounds for rejecting ballots.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The Quebec government also changed the Electoral Act so that voters would need to show a Canadian passport, Quebec driver's licence or Quebec provincial health care card at the polling station for identification purposes in future elections.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Parizeau's resignation led to Bouchard becoming the leader of the PQ and premier unopposed.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] While Bouchard maintained a third referendum was forthcoming provided "winning conditions" occurred, his government's chief priority became reform of the Quebec economy.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Daniel Johnson would resign as leader of the Liberal Party of Quebec, and after significant pressure in English Canada, Charest resigned as national PC leader and was acclaimed as leader of the Quebec Liberals.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Observers expected Bouchard to announce another sovereignty referendum if his party won the 1998 Quebec general election.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] While he defeated Charest, Bouchard continued his government's focus on Quebec's economy.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Bouchard retired in 2001 and was replaced by Bernard Landry who, despite promising a more robust stance on the sovereignty issue, was ousted in the 2003 Quebec general election by Charest, who would become premier.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] After the referendum, Chrétien attempted to pursue constitutional recognition of distinct society, but was stopped by the blunt refusal of Ontario Premier Mike Harris to discuss any constitutional matters due to his perception they had dominated the country's debates for too long.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Given the impossibility of any meaningful change without Ontario's approval, Chrétien opted to pursue unilateral federal changes to fulfill his government's referendum commitments.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] This included legislation which required permission from the provinces of Quebec, Ontario and British Columbia for federal approval to be granted to any constitutional amendment, granting Quebec a *de facto* veto.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The Federal parliament also officially recognized Quebec as a distinct society.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Both changes, not being constitutional amendments, are theoretically reversible by future parliaments.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Chrétien also pursued what he called "Plan B" in hopes of convincing Quebec voters that economic and legal obstacles would follow if Quebec were to declare itself sovereign; its public face would become professor Stéphane Dion.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] After the decision, the Liberal government passed the Clarity Act, which stated that any future referendum would have to be on a "clear question" and that it would have to represent a "clear majority" for the federal Parliament to recognize its validity.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Section 1(4) of the act stated that questions that provided for only a mandate for negotiation or envisioned other partnerships with Canada would be considered unclear, and thus not recognized.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] The National Assembly of Quebec passed Bill 99, proclaiming the right of self-determination and the right of the National Assembly to set referendum questions pursuant to the *Referendum Act* and to declare the winning majority in a referendum as a simple majority of 50% plus 1 vote.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Bill 99's constitutionality was litigated for 25 years, until the Quebec Court of Appeal ruled in 2021 that the law, given its general wording, was constitutional when applied within provincial jurisdiction.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] Following the narrow victory, the Chrétien government established a Federal government-funded advertising campaign to promote national symbols and sponsor hunting, fishing and other recreational events to promote Canada within Quebec.
[src:canada/1995-quebec-referendum-p02] This eventually led to the Gomery Commission's investigation of the Sponsorship Scandal.
[src:canada/ca] Registrants can register domains at the second level (e.g., *example.ca*).
[src:canada/ca] Third-level registrations in one of the geographic third-level domains defined by the registry (e.g.
[src:canada/ca] *example.ab.ca*) were discontinued on October 12, 2010, but existing third-level domain names continue to be supported.
[src:canada/ca] Registrants of .ca domains must meet the Canadian Presence Requirements as defined by the registry.
[src:canada/ca] The domain name was originally allocated by Jon Postel, operator of Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA), to John Demco of the University of British Columbia (UBC) in 1987.
[src:canada/ca] The first .ca domain was registered by the University of Prince Edward Island in January 1988.
[src:canada/ca] In 1997, at the Canadian annual Internet conference in Halifax, Nova Scotia, the Canadian Internet community, with a view to liberalize registration procedures and substantially improve turnaround times, decided to undertake reform of the .ca Registry.
[src:canada/ca] The Canadian Internet Registration Authority (CIRA) is a non-profit Canadian corporation that is responsible for operating the .ca Internet country code Top Level Domain (ccTLD) today.
[src:canada/ca] It assumed operation of the .ca ccTLD on December 1, 2000, from UBC.
[src:canada/ca] On April 15, 2008, CIRA registered its one millionth .ca Internet domain name.
[src:canada/ca] Any .ca registration has to be ordered via a certified registrar.
[src:canada/ca] UBC's registry operations once favoured fourth-level names (such as city.toronto.on.ca) for purely local entities or third-level names for entities operating solely within one province.
[src:canada/ca] Nationally incorporated companies could have a *.ca* domain, while provincially incorporated companies required the letters of their province, like *.mb.ca*.
[src:canada/ca] Only an entity with presence in two or more provinces was typically registered directly under .ca; this complex structure (and the long delays in getting .ca registration) caused many Canadian entities to favour the .com, .org and .net registrations, despite the then-higher cost.
[src:canada/ca] Currently, any of the above listed parties can register a domain with a name of their choosing followed directly by *.ca*.
[src:canada/ca] CIRA stopped accepting new registrations for third-level domains on October 12, 2010, citing complexity and the low number of new third domain registration as the reason for the change.
[src:canada/ca] The second-level domain name '.gc.ca' (Government of Canada) is commonly mistaken as one of the regional domains under which CIRA will allow Government of Canada registrations. gc.ca is actually a standard domain like all other .ca domain names.
[src:canada/ca] CIRA does not register domain names under .gc.ca directly.
[src:canada/ca] The .mil.ca second-level domain name is also a standard domain and is registered to the Department of National Defence (DND).
[src:canada/ca] The .mil.ca suffix is used internally by DND on its intranet, the Defence Information Network (DIN) or Defence Wide Area Network (DWAN), to distinguish intranet-only websites.
[src:canada/ca] Internationalized domain names (IDN) were introduced in January 2013 with a limited selection of characters (é, ë, ê, è, â, à, æ, ô, œ, ù, û, ü, ç, î, ï, ÿ) to allow French language text with diacritics.
[src:canada/ca] Names which differ only in diacritical accents (such as metro.ca and métro.ca) must have the same owner and same registrar.
[src:canada/ca] Domain names that begin with the four characters xn-- are otherwise not available for registration.
[src:canada/ca] Length must be 2-63 characters, including the xn-- prefix encoding for internationalized domain names.
[src:canada/ca] Names which match the name of an existing generic three-letter top level domain (such as .com.ca) or the Canadian top level country code (.ca) are reserved and therefore not available for new registrations.
[src:canada/ca] Certain expletives are not accepted as names.
[src:canada/ca] Municipal names of individual cities and localities within Canada are also reserved nationwide, along with village.ca, hamlet.ca, town.ca, city.ca, ville.ca and the names of Canadian provinces.
[src:canada/ca] There are a handful of existing .ca registered names as short as two characters in length, but these tend to be rare as two-letter combinations matching any existing country-code TLDs were reserved in the past.
[src:canada/ca] Exceptions were typically names registered before the restriction was introduced, such as the Canadian Governor General at gg.ca.
[src:canada/ca] Names which exist at any of the levels (.ca, an individual province or territory, or an individual city) are blocked in their availability elsewhere in the .ca hierarchy.
[src:canada/ca] Registration, if it can be done at all, requires manual intervention by the prospective registrar as the permission of all existing registrant(s) must be obtained by CIRA.
[src:canada/ca] Since Ontario, Prince Edward Island and Quebec already use "gouv" on their provincial second-level domains for the French-language versions of their government websites, this domain is unavailable through the normal registration process.
[src:canada/ca] However, with the agreement of these three parties New Brunswick would indeed be able to register and use gouv.nb.ca.
[src:canada/ca] Existing third-level domain registrants looking to obtain the corresponding second-level domain are normally advised to use the same initial registrar for both names.
[src:canada/ca] After a thirty-day redemption period, intended to provide the original registrant one final chance to reclaim a suspended name, the expired names are assigned a to-be-released (TBR) status.
[src:canada/ca] These names are made available through a weekly auction process, in which lists of available names are posted online and advance bids are placed by prospective registrants through the various .ca registrars.
[src:canada/ca] Domains which receive no bids are then released and made openly available for new registrations.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples have continuously inhabited what is now Canada for thousands of years.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Beginning in the 16th century, British and French expeditions explored and later settled along the Atlantic coast.
[src:canada/canada-p01] As a consequence of various armed conflicts, France ceded nearly all of its colonies in North America in 1763.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1867, with the union of three British North American colonies through Confederation, Canada was formed as a federal dominion of four provinces.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This began an accretion of provinces and territories resulting in the displacement of Indigenous populations, and a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This increased sovereignty was highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and culminated in the *Canada Act 1982*, which severed the vestiges of legal dependence on the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy in the Westminster tradition.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country's head of government is the prime minister, who holds office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the elected House of Commons and is appointed by the governor general, representing the monarch of Canada, the ceremonial head of state.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country is a Commonwealth realm and is officially bilingual (English and French) in the federal jurisdiction.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It is very highly ranked in international measurements of government transparency, quality of life, economic competitiveness, innovation, education and human rights.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It is one of the world's most ethnically diverse and multicultural nations, the product of large-scale immigration.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's long and complex relationship with the United States has had a significant impact on its history, economy, and culture.
[src:canada/canada-p01] A developed country, Canada has a high nominal per capita income globally and its advanced economy ranks among the largest in the world by nominal GDP, relying chiefly upon its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade networks.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power; its support for multilateralism and internationalism has been closely related to its foreign policies of peacekeeping and aid for developing countries.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participation in multiple international organizations and forums.
[src:canada/canada-p01] While a variety of theories have been postulated for the etymological origins of *Canada*, the name is now accepted as coming from the St.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Lawrence Iroquoian word *kanata*, meaning 'village' or 'settlement'.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1535, Indigenous inhabitants of the present-day Quebec City region used the word to direct French explorer Jacques Cartier to the village of Stadacona.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Cartier later used the word *Canada* to refer not only to that particular village but to the entire area subject to Donnacona (the chief at Stadacona); by 1545, European books and maps had begun referring to this small region along the Saint Lawrence River as *Canada*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] From the 16th to the early 18th century, *Canada* referred to the part of New France that lay along the Saint Lawrence River.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Following the British conquest of New France, this area was known as the British Province of Quebec from 1763 to 1791.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1791, the area became two British colonies called Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] These two colonies were collectively referred to as the Canadas until their union as the Province of Canada in 1841.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Upon Confederation in 1867, *Canada* was adopted as the legal name for the new country at the London Conference and the word *dominion* was conferred as the country's title, reflecting its status as a self-governing nation within the British Empire.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Following the London Declaration of 1949, where it was agreed that India could be a full member of the Commonwealth as a republic, not a dominion, the leaders of the Commonwealth countries agreed that the other members of the Commonwealth should not continue to be referred to as *dominions*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Laurent announced in the Canadian House of Commons that in light of the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and the changes to the Commonwealth, *dominion* was no longer an accurate term to use to refer to Canada and would no longer be used by the federal government.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Similarly, the United Kingdom no longer used the term *dominions* to refer to Canada or other members of the Commonwealth, instead beginning to use the term a *realm of the Commonwealth*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The *Canada Act 1982*, which brought the Constitution of Canada fully under Canadian control, referred only to *Canada*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Later that year, the name of the national holiday was changed from Dominion Day to Canada Day.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The first inhabitants of North America are generally hypothesized to have migrated from Siberia by way of the Bering land bridge and arrived at least 14,000 years ago.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Paleo-Indian archeological sites at Old Crow Flats and Bluefish Caves are two of the oldest sites of human habitation in Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The characteristics of Indigenous societies included permanent settlements, agriculture, complex societal hierarchies, and trading networks.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Some of these cultures had collapsed by the time European explorers arrived in the late 15th and early 16th centuries and have only been discovered through archeological investigations.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples in present-day Canada include the First Nations, Inuit, and Métis, the last being of mixed descent who originated in the mid-17th century when First Nations people married European settlers and their offspring subsequently developed their own identity.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Indigenous population at the time of the first European settlements is estimated to have been between 200,000 and two million, with a figure of 500,000 accepted by Canada's Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples.
[src:canada/canada-p01] As a consequence of European colonization, the Indigenous population declined by forty to eighty percent.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Although not without conflict, European Canadians' early interactions with First Nations and Inuit populations were relatively peaceful.
[src:canada/canada-p01] First Nations and Métis peoples played a critical part in the development of European colonies in Canada, particularly for their role in assisting European coureurs des bois and voyageurs in their explorations of the continent during the North American fur trade.
[src:canada/canada-p01] These early European interactions with First Nations would change from friendship and peace treaties to the dispossession of Indigenous lands through treaties.
[src:canada/canada-p01] From the late 18th century, European Canadians forced Indigenous peoples to assimilate into a western Canadian society.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Settler colonialism reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:canada/canada-p01] A period of redress began with the formation of a reconciliation commission by the Government of Canada in 2008.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This included acknowledgment of cultural genocide, settlement agreements, and betterment of racial discrimination issues, such as addressing the plight of missing and murdered Indigenous women.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It is believed that the first documented European to explore the east coast of Canada was Norse explorer Leif Erikson.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In approximately 1000 AD, the Norse built a small short-lived encampment that was occupied sporadically for perhaps 20 years at L'Anse aux Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland.
[src:canada/canada-p01] No further European exploration occurred until 1497, when seafarer John Cabot explored and claimed Canada's Atlantic coast in the name of Henry VII of England.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1534, French explorer Jacques Cartier explored the Gulf of Saint Lawrence where, on July 24, he planted a 10-metre (33 ft) cross bearing the words, "long live the King of France", and took possession of the territory New France in the name of King Francis I.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The early 16th century saw European mariners with navigational techniques pioneered by the Basque and Portuguese establish seasonal whaling and fishing outposts along the Atlantic coast.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In general, early settlements during the Age of Discovery appear to have been short-lived due to a combination of the harsh climate, problems with navigating trade routes and competing outputs in Scandinavia.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1583, Sir Humphrey Gilbert, by the royal prerogative of Queen Elizabeth I, founded St John's, Newfoundland, as the first North American English seasonal camp.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1600, the French established their first seasonal trading post at Tadoussac along the Saint Lawrence.
[src:canada/canada-p01] French explorer Samuel de Champlain arrived in 1603 and established the first permanent year-round European settlements at Port Royal (in 1605) and Quebec City (in 1608).
[src:canada/canada-p01] Among the colonists of New France, *Canadiens* extensively settled the Saint Lawrence River valley and Acadians settled the present-day Maritimes, while fur traders and Catholic missionaries explored the Great Lakes, Hudson Bay, and the Mississippi watershed to Louisiana.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Beaver Wars broke out in the mid-17th century over control of the North American fur trade.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The English established additional settlements in Newfoundland in 1610 along with settlements in the Thirteen Colonies to the south.
[src:canada/canada-p01] A series of four wars erupted in colonial North America between 1689 and 1763; the later wars of the period constituted the North American theatre of the Seven Years' War.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Mainland Nova Scotia came under British rule with the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht and Canada and most of New France came under British rule in 1763 after the Seven Years' War.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 established First Nation treaty rights, created the Province of Quebec out of New France, and annexed Cape Breton Island to Nova Scotia.
[src:canada/canada-p01] St John's Island (now Prince Edward Island) became a separate colony in 1769.
[src:canada/canada-p01] To avert conflict in Quebec, the British Parliament passed the Quebec Act 1774, expanding Quebec's territory to the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
[src:canada/canada-p01] More importantly, the Quebec Act afforded Quebec special autonomy and rights of self-administration at a time when the Thirteen Colonies were increasingly agitating against British rule.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It re-established the French language, Catholic faith, and French civil law there, staving off the growth of an independence movement in contrast to the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Proclamation and the Quebec Act in turn angered many residents of the Thirteen Colonies, further fuelling anti-British sentiment in the years prior to the American Revolution.
[src:canada/canada-p01] After the American War of Independence, the 1783 Treaty of Paris recognized the independence of the United States and set the terms of peace, ceding British North American territories south of the Great Lakes and east of the Mississippi River to the new country.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The American war of independence also caused a large out-migration of Loyalists, the settlers who had fought against American independence.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Many moved to Canada, particularly Atlantic Canada, where their arrival changed the demographic distribution of the existing territories.
[src:canada/canada-p01] New Brunswick was in turn split from Nova Scotia as part of a reorganization of Loyalist settlements in the Maritimes, which led to the incorporation of Saint John, New Brunswick, as Canada's first city.
[src:canada/canada-p01] To accommodate the influx of English-speaking Loyalists in Central Canada, the Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the province of Canada into French-speaking Lower Canada (later Quebec) and English-speaking Upper Canada (later Ontario), granting each its own elected legislative assembly.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Canadas were the main front in the War of 1812 between the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Peace came in 1815; no boundaries were changed.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Immigration resumed at a higher level, with over 960,000 arrivals from Britain between 1815 and 1850.
[src:canada/canada-p01] New arrivals included refugees escaping the Great Irish Famine as well as Gaelic-speaking Scots displaced by the Highland Clearances.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Infectious diseases killed between 25 and 33 percent of Europeans who immigrated to Canada before 1891.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The desire for responsible government resulted in the abortive Rebellions of 1837.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Durham Report subsequently recommended responsible government and the assimilation of French Canadians into English culture.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Act of Union 1840 merged the Canadas into a united Province of Canada and responsible government was established for all provinces of British North America east of Lake Superior by 1855.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The signing of the Oregon Treaty by Britain and the United States in 1846 ended the Oregon boundary dispute, extending the border westward along the 49th parallel.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This paved the way for British colonies on Vancouver Island (1849) and in British Columbia (1858).
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Anglo-Russian Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1825) established the border along the Pacific coast, but, even after the US Alaska Purchase of 1867, disputes continued about the exact demarcation of the Alaska–Yukon and Alaska–British Columbia border.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Following three constitutional conferences, the *British North America Act, 1867* officially proclaimed Canadian Confederation on July 1, 1867, initially with four provinces: Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada assumed control of Rupert's Land and the North-Western Territory to form the Northwest Territories, where the Métis' grievances ignited the Red River Rebellion and the creation of the province of Manitoba in July 1870.
[src:canada/canada-p01] British Columbia and Vancouver Island (which had been united in 1866) joined the confederation in 1871 on the promise of a transcontinental railway extending to Victoria in the province within 10 years, while Prince Edward Island joined in 1873.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1898, during the Klondike Gold Rush in the Northwest Territories, Parliament created the Yukon Territory.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Alberta and Saskatchewan became provinces in 1905.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Between 1871 and 1896, almost one quarter of the Canadian population emigrated south to the US.
[src:canada/canada-p01] To settle the West and attract European immigrants, Canada sponsored the construction of three transcontinental railways, enacted the *Dominion Lands Act* and founded the North-West Mounted Police to maintain regional authority.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This period of westward expansion and nation building resulted in the displacement of many Indigenous peoples of the Canadian Prairies to "Indian reserves", clearing the way for ethnic European block settlements.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This caused the collapse of the Plains Bison in western Canada and the introduction of European cattle farms and wheat fields dominating the land.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Indigenous peoples saw widespread famine and disease due to the loss of the bison and their traditional hunting lands.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The federal government did provide emergency relief, on condition of the Indigenous peoples moving to the reserves.
[src:canada/canada-p01] During this time, Canada introduced the *Indian Act* extending its control over the First Nations to education, government and legal rights.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Because Britain still maintained control of Canada's foreign affairs under the British North America Act, 1867, its declaration of war in 1914 automatically brought Canada into the First World War.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Volunteers sent to the Western Front later became part of the Canadian Corps, which played a substantial role in the Battle of Vimy Ridge and other major engagements of the war.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Conscription Crisis of 1917 erupted when the Unionist Cabinet's proposal to augment the military's dwindling number of active members with conscription was met with vehement objections from French-speaking Quebecers.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1919, Canada joined the League of Nations independently of Britain.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Great Depression in Canada during the early 1930s saw an economic downturn, leading to hardship across the country.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In response to the downturn, the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) in Saskatchewan introduced many elements of a welfare state (as pioneered by Tommy Douglas) in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:canada/canada-p01] On the advice of Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, war with Germany was declared effective September 10, 1939, by King George VI, seven days after the United Kingdom.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The delay underscored Canada's independence.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The first Canadian Army units arrived in Britain in December 1939.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In all, over a million Canadians served in the armed forces during the Second World War.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canadian troops played important roles in many key battles of the war, including the failed 1942 Dieppe Raid, the Allied invasion of Italy, the Normandy landings, the Battle of Normandy, and the Battle of the Scheldt in 1944.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada provided asylum for the Dutch monarchy while that country was occupied and is credited by the Netherlands for major contributions to its liberation from Nazi Germany.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Despite another conscription crisis in Quebec in 1944, Canada finished the war with a large army and strong economy.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The financial crisis of the Great Depression led the Dominion of Newfoundland to relinquish responsible government in 1934 and become a Crown colony ruled by a British governor.
[src:canada/canada-p01] After two referendums, Newfoundlanders voted to join Canada in 1949 as a province.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Socially democratic programs were also instituted, such as Medicare, the Canada Pension Plan, and Canada Student Loans; though, provincial governments, particularly Quebec and Alberta, opposed many of these as incursions into their jurisdictions.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Finally, another series of constitutional conferences resulted in the *Canada Act 1982*, the patriation of Canada's constitution from the United Kingdom, concurrent with the creation of the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada had established complete sovereignty as an independent country under its own monarchy.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1999, Nunavut became Canada's third territory after a series of negotiations with the federal government.
[src:canada/canada-p01] At the same time, Quebec underwent profound social and economic changes through the Quiet Revolution of the 1960s, giving birth to a secular nationalist movement.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The radical Front de libération du Québec (FLQ) ignited the October Crisis with a series of bombings and kidnappings in 1970, and the sovereigntist Parti Québécois was elected in 1976, organizing an unsuccessful referendum on sovereignty-association in 1980.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Attempts to accommodate Quebec nationalism constitutionally through the Meech Lake Accord failed in 1990.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This led to the formation of the Bloc Québécois in Quebec and the invigoration of the Reform Party of Canada in the West.
[src:canada/canada-p01] A second referendum followed in 1995, in which sovereignty was rejected by a slimmer margin of 50.6 to 49.4 percent.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled unilateral secession by a province would be unconstitutional, and the Clarity Act was passed by Parliament, outlining the terms of a negotiated departure from Confederation.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In addition to the issues of Quebec sovereignty, a number of crises shook Canadian society in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada joined the Gulf War in 1990 and was active in several peacekeeping missions in the 1990s, including operations in the Balkans during and after the Yugoslav Wars, and in Somalia, resulting in an incident that has been described as "the darkest era in the history of the Canadian military".
[src:canada/canada-p01] After the September 11 attacks in the United States, Canada sent troops to Afghanistan in 2001, resulting in the largest amount of Canadian deaths for any single military mission since the Korean War in the early 1950s.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 2011, Canadian forces participated in the NATO-led intervention into the Libyan Civil War and also became involved in battling the Islamic State insurgency in Iraq in the mid-2010s.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Canada began on January 27, 2020, causing widespread social and economic disruption.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 2021, possible gravesites of Indigenous children were found near former Canadian residential schools, highlighting the cultural genocide against Indigenous peoples.
[src:canada/canada-p01] A trade war involving the United States began on February 1, 2025, when U.S. president Donald Trump signed orders imposing tariffs on goods entering the United States, alongside rhetoric suggesting the annexation of Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] By total area (including its waters), Canada is the second-largest country.
[src:canada/canada-p01] By land area alone, Canada ranks fourth, due to having the world's largest area of fresh water lakes.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Stretching from the Atlantic Ocean in the east, along the Arctic Ocean to the north, and to the Pacific Ocean in the west, the country encompasses 9,984,670 square kilometres (3,855,100 sq mi) of territory.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is also home to the world's northernmost settlement, Canadian Forces Station Alert, on the northern tip of Ellesmere Island—latitude 82.5°N—which lies 817 kilometres (508 mi) from the North Pole.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In latitude, Canada's most northerly point of land is Cape Columbia in Nunavut at 83°6′41″N, with its southern extreme at Middle Island in Lake Erie at 41°40′53″N.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In longitude, Canada's land extends from Cape Spear, Newfoundland, at 52°37′W, to Mount St.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada can be divided into seven physiographic regions: the Canadian Shield, the Interior Plains, the Great Lakes–St.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Lawrence Lowlands, the Appalachian region, the Western Cordillera, Hudson Bay Lowlands, and the Arctic Archipelago.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Boreal forests prevail throughout the country, ice is prominent in northern Arctic regions and through the Rocky Mountains, and the relatively flat Canadian Prairies in the southwest facilitate productive agriculture.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Lawrence River (in the southeast) where the lowlands host much of Canada's economic output.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has over 2,000,000 lakes—563 of which are larger than 100 square kilometres (39 sq mi)—containing much of the world's fresh water.
[src:canada/canada-p01] There are also fresh-water glaciers in the Canadian Rockies, the Coast Mountains, and the Arctic Cordillera.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is geologically active, having many earthquakes and potentially active volcanoes.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Average winter and summer high temperatures across Canada vary from region to region.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Winters can be harsh in many parts of the country, particularly in the interior and Prairie provinces, which experience a continental climate, where daily average temperatures are near −15 °C (5 °F), but can drop below −40 °C (−40 °F) with severe wind chills.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In non-coastal regions, snow can cover the ground for almost six months of the year, while in parts of the north snow can persist year-round.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Coastal British Columbia has a temperate climate, with a mild and rainy winter.
[src:canada/canada-p01] On the east and west coasts, average high temperatures are generally in the low 20s °C (70s °F), while between the coasts, the average summer high temperature ranges from 25 to 30 °C (77 to 86 °F), with temperatures in some interior locations occasionally exceeding 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:canada/canada-p01] Much of Northern Canada is covered by ice and permafrost.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The future of the permafrost is uncertain because the Arctic has been warming at three times the global average as a result of climate change in Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's annual average temperature over land has risen by 1.7 °C (3.1 °F), with changes ranging from 1.1 to 2.3 °C (2.0 to 4.1 °F) in various regions, since 1948.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The rate of warming has been higher across the North and in the Prairies.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In the southern regions of Canada, air pollution from both Canada and the United States—caused by metal smelting, burning coal to power utilities, and vehicle emissions—has resulted in acid rain, which has severely impacted waterways, forest growth, and agricultural productivity.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is one of the largest greenhouse gas emitters globally, with emissions increased by 16.5 percent between 1990 and 2022.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is divided into 15 terrestrial and five marine ecozones.
[src:canada/canada-p01] These ecozones encompass over 80,000 classified species of Canadian wildlife, with an equal number yet to be formally recognized or discovered.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Although Canada has a low percentage of endemic species compared to other countries, due to human activities, invasive species, and environmental issues in the country, there are currently more than 800 species at risk of being lost.
[src:canada/canada-p01] About 65 percent of Canada's resident species are considered "Secure".
[src:canada/canada-p01] Over half of Canada's landscape is intact and relatively free of human development.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The boreal forest of Canada is considered to be the largest intact forest on Earth, with approximately 3,000,000 square kilometres (1,200,000 sq mi) undisturbed by roads, cities or industry.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Since the end of the last glacial period, Canada has consisted of eight distinct forest regions.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Approximately 12.1 percent of the nation's landmass and freshwater are conservation areas, including 11.4 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Approximately 13.8 percent of its territorial waters are conserved, including 8.9 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's first National Park, Banff National Park was established in 1885.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's oldest provincial park, Algonquin Provincial Park was established in 1893.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Established in 2015, Lake Superior National Marine Conservation Area is the world's largest freshwater protected area.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's largest national wildlife region, established in 2018, is the Scott Islands Marine National Wildlife Area.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is described as a "full democracy", with a tradition of liberalism, and an egalitarian, moderate political ideology.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Since the 1960s, an emphasis on social justice has been a distinguishing element of Canada's political culture.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Peace, order, and good government, alongside an Implied Bill of Rights, are founding principles of Canadian federalism.
[src:canada/canada-p01] At the federal level, Canada has been dominated by two relatively centrist parties practising "brokerage politics": the centre-left leaning Liberal Party of Canada and the centre-right leaning Conservative Party of Canada (or its predecessors).
[src:canada/canada-p01] The historically predominant Liberals position themselves at the centre of the political scale.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Far-right and far-left politics have never been a prominent force in Canadian society.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has a parliamentary system within the context of a constitutional monarchy—the monarchy of Canada being the foundation of the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The reigning monarch is also monarch of 14 other sovereign Commonwealth countries and Canada's 10 provinces.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The monarch appoints a representative, the governor general, on the advice of the prime minister, to carry out most of their ceremonial royal duties.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The monarchy is the source of sovereignty and authority in Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] To ensure the stability of government, the governor general will usually appoint as prime minister the person who is the current leader of the political party that can obtain the confidence of a majority of members in the House.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The leader of the party with the second-most seats usually becomes the leader of the Official Opposition and is part of an adversarial parliamentary system intended to keep the government in check.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Parliament of Canada passes all federal statute laws.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It comprises the monarch, the House of Commons, and the Senate.
[src:canada/canada-p01] While Canada inherited the British concept of parliamentary supremacy, this was later, with the enactment of the Constitution Act, 1982, all but completely superseded by the American notion of the supremacy of the law.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Each of the 343 members of Parliament in the House of Commons is elected by simple plurality in an electoral district or riding.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The 105 members of the Senate, whose seats are apportioned on a regional basis, serve until age 75.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canadian federalism divides government responsibilities between the federal government and the 10 provinces.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Provincial legislatures are unicameral and operate in parliamentary fashion similar to the House of Commons.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's three territories also have legislatures, but these are not sovereign, have fewer constitutional responsibilities than the provinces, and differ structurally from their provincial counterparts.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Constitution of Canada is the supreme law of the country and consists of written text and unwritten conventions.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The *Constitution Act, 1867* (known as the British North America Act, 1867 prior to 1982), affirmed governance based on parliamentary precedent and divided powers between the federal and provincial governments.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, granted full autonomy, and the *Constitution Act, 1982*, ended all legislative ties to Britain, as well as adding a constitutional amending formula and the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The *Charter* guarantees basic rights and freedoms that usually cannot be overridden by any government; a notwithstanding clause allows Parliament and the provincial legislatures to override certain sections of the *Charter* for a period of five years.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's judiciary interprets laws and has the power to strike down acts of Parliament that violate the constitution.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Supreme Court of Canada is the highest court, final arbiter, and has been led since 2017 by Richard Wagner, the Chief Justice of Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The governor general appoints the court's nine members on the advice of the prime minister and minister of justice.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The federal Cabinet also appoints justices to superior courts in the provincial and territorial jurisdictions.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Common law prevails everywhere except Quebec, where civil law predominates.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Criminal law is solely a federal responsibility and is uniform throughout Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Law enforcement, including criminal courts, is officially a provincial responsibility, conducted by provincial and municipal police forces.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In most rural and some urban areas, policing responsibilities are contracted to the federal Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canadian Aboriginal law provides certain constitutionally recognized rights to land and traditional practices for Indigenous groups in Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Various treaties and case laws were established to mediate relations between Europeans and many Indigenous peoples.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The role of Aboriginal law and the rights they support were reaffirmed by section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982.
[src:canada/canada-p01] These rights may include provision of services, such as healthcare through the Indian Health Transfer Policy, and exemption from taxation.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is a federation composed of 10 federated states, called provinces, and three federal territories.
[src:canada/canada-p01] These may be grouped into four main regions: Western Canada, Central Canada, Atlantic Canada, and Northern Canada (*Eastern Canada* refers to Central Canada and Atlantic Canada together).
[src:canada/canada-p01] Provinces and territories have responsibility for social programs such as healthcare, education, and social programs, as well as administration of justice (but not criminal law).
[src:canada/canada-p01] Although the provinces collect more revenue than the federal government, equalization payments are made by the federal government to ensure reasonably uniform standards of services and taxation are kept between the richer and poorer provinces.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power for its role in global affairs with a tendency to pursue multilateral and international solutions.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Globalization has significantly influenced Canadian foreign policies, with the country known for its promotion of peace and security through mediation, and for providing aid to developing countries.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada and the United States have a long and complex relationship; historically close allies, they co-operate regularly on military campaigns and humanitarian efforts.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada also maintains historic and traditional ties to the United Kingdom and to France, along with both countries' former colonies through its membership in the Commonwealth of Nations and the *Organisation internationale de la Francophonie*.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is noted for having a positive relationship with the Netherlands, owing, in part, to its contribution to the Dutch liberation during the Second World War.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has diplomatic and consular offices in over 270 locations in approximately 180 foreign countries.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participating in multiple international organizations.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada was a founding member of the United Nations (UN) in 1945 and formed the North American Aerospace Defense Command together with the United States in 1958.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country has membership in the World Trade Organization, the Five Eyes, the G7 and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD).
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country was a founding member of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) in 1989 and joined the Organization of American States (OAS) in 1990.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada ratified the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) in 1948, and seven principal UN human rights conventions and covenants since then.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Alongside many domestic obligations, more than 3,000 Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) personnel are deployed in multiple foreign military operations.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Canadian unified forces comprise the Royal Canadian Navy, Canadian Army, and Royal Canadian Air Force.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The nation employs a professional, volunteer force of approximately 68,000 active personnel and 27,000 reserve personnel.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In March 2026, Canada achieved the NATO target of spending 2% of its GDP on defence for the 2026 fiscal year.
[src:canada/canada-p01] This marks a significant increase from previous years—roughly 1.3% to 1.4% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's role in developing *peacekeeping* and its participation in initiatives during the 20th century has played a major role in its positive global image.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Peacekeeping is deeply embedded in Canadian culture and a distinguishing feature that Canadians feel sets their foreign policy apart from the United States.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has long been reluctant to participate in military interventions that are not sanctioned by the United Nations, such as the Vietnam War, the 2003 invasion of Iraq and 2026 Iran war.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Since the 21st century, Canadian direct participation in UN peacekeeping efforts has greatly declined.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The large decrease was a result of Canada directing its participation to UN-sanctioned military operations through the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, rather than directly through the UN.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The change to participation via NATO has resulted in a shift towards more militarized and deadly missions rather than traditional peacekeeping duties.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's mixed-market economy is highly developed, ranking as the world's ninth-largest by nominal GDP as of 2023, at approximately US$2.221 trillion.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country is one of the world's largest trading nations, with a highly globalized economy.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 2021, Canadian trade in goods and services reached $2.016 trillion.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's exports totalled over $637 billion, while its imported goods were worth over $631 billion, of which approximately $391 billion originated from the United States.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 2018, Canada had a trade deficit in goods of $22 billion and a trade deficit in services of $25 billion.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Toronto Stock Exchange is the ninth-largest stock exchange in the world by market capitalization, listing over 1,500 companies with a combined market capitalization of over US$2 trillion.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Bank of Canada is the central bank of the country.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The minister of finance and minister of innovation, science, and industry use data from Statistics Canada to enable financial planning and develop economic policy.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has a strong cooperative banking sector, with the world's highest per-capita membership in credit unions.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It ranks low in the Corruption Perceptions Index (14th in 2023) and "is widely regarded as among the least corrupt countries of the world".
[src:canada/canada-p01] It ranks high in the Global Competitiveness Report (19th in 2024).
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's economy ranks above most Western nations on the Heritage Foundation's Index of Economic Freedom and experiences a relatively low level of income disparity.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country's average household disposable income per capita is "well above" the OECD average.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada ranks among the lowest of the most developed countries for housing affordability and foreign direct investment.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The unemployment rate in 2025 was 6.8 percent.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Since the early 20th century, the growth of Canada's manufacturing, mining, and service sectors has transformed the nation from a largely rural economy to an urbanized, industrial one.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Canadian economy is dominated by the service industry, which employs about three-quarters of the country's workforce.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has an unusually important primary sector, of which the forestry and petroleum industries are the most prominent components.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Many towns in northern Canada, where agriculture is difficult, are sustained by nearby mines or sources of timber.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's economic integration with the United States has increased significantly since the Second World War.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Canada – United States Free Trade Agreement (FTA) of 1988 eliminated tariffs between the two countries, while the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) expanded the free-trade zone to include Mexico in 1994 (later replaced by the Canada–United States–Mexico Agreement).
[src:canada/canada-p01] As of 2023, Canada is a signatory to 15 free trade agreements with 51 different countries.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is one of the few developed nations that are net exporters of energy.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Atlantic Canada possess vast offshore deposits of natural gas, and Alberta hosts the fourth-largest oil reserves in the world.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The vast Athabasca oil sands and other oil reserves give Canada 13 percent of global oil reserves, constituting the world's third- or fourth-largest.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada is additionally one of the world's largest suppliers of agricultural products; the Canadian Prairies region is one of the most important global producers of wheat, canola, and other grains.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's main exports are zinc, uranium, gold, nickel, platinoids, aluminum, steel, iron ore, coking coal, lead, copper, molybdenum, cobalt, and cadmium.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has a sizeable manufacturing sector centred in southern Ontario and Quebec, with automobiles and aeronautics representing particularly important industries.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country's fishing and tourism industries are also a key contributor to the economy.
[src:canada/canada-p01] In 2020, Canada spent approximately $41.9 billion on domestic research and development, with supplementary estimates for 2022 at $43.2 billion.
[src:canada/canada-p01] As of 2023, the country has produced 15 Nobel laureates in physics, chemistry, and medicine.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The country ranks seventh in the worldwide share of articles published in scientific journals, according to the Nature Index, and is home to the headquarters of a number of global technology firms.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has one of the highest levels of Internet access in the world, with approximately 95 percent of its population aged 15 and above.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada's achievements in science and technology include the creation of the modern alkaline battery, the discovery of insulin, the development of the polio vaccine, and discoveries about the interior structure of the atomic nucleus.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Other major Canadian scientific contributions include the artificial cardiac pacemaker, mapping the visual cortex, the development of the electron microscope, plate tectonics, deep learning, multi-touch technology, and the identification of the first black hole, Cygnus X-1.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has a long history of discovery in genetics, which include stem cells, site-directed mutagenesis, T-cell receptor, and the identification of the genes that cause Fanconi anemia, cystic fibrosis, and early-onset Alzheimer's disease, among numerous other diseases.
[src:canada/canada-p01] The Canadian Space Agency runs an active space program focused on deep-space, planetary, and aviation research, along with rockets and satellites.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada launched its first satellite, Alouette 1, in 1962.
[src:canada/canada-p01] It contributes to the International Space Station and is known for its robotic tools, such as multiple Canadarms.
[src:canada/canada-p01] Canada has initiated many long-term projects, including the Radarsat satellite series and the Black Brant rocket series.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The 2021 Canadian census enumerated a total population of 36,991,981, an increase of around 5.2 percent over the 2016 figure.
[src:canada/canada-p02] It is estimated that Canada's population surpassed 40,000,000 in 2023.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The main drivers of population growth are immigration and, to a lesser extent, natural growth.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest per-capita immigration rates in the world, driven mainly by economic policy and family reunification.
[src:canada/canada-p02] A record 483,390 immigrants were admitted in 2024.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada leads the world in refugee resettlement; it resettled more than 47,600 in 2022.
[src:canada/canada-p02] New immigrants settle mostly in major urban areas, such as Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada's population density, at 4.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (11/sq mi), is among the lowest in the world, with approximately 95 percent of the population residing south of the 55th parallel north.
[src:canada/canada-p02] About 80 percent of the population lives within 150 kilometres (93 mi) of the border with the contiguous United States.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada is highly urbanized, with over 80 percent of the population living in urban centres.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (over 70 percent) live below the 49th parallel, with 50 percent of Canadians living south of 45°42′ (45.7 degrees) north.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The most densely populated part of the country is the Quebec City–Windsor Corridor in Southern Quebec and Southern Ontario along the Great Lakes and the St.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (81.1 percent) live in family households, 12.1 percent report living alone, and 6.8 percent live with other relatives or unrelated persons.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Fifty-one percent of households are couples with or without children, 8.7 percent are single-parent households, 2.9 percent are multigenerational households, and 29.3 percent are single-person households.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Respondents in the 2021 Canadian census self-reported over 450 "ethnic or cultural origins".
[src:canada/canada-p02] Over 60 percent of Canadians reported a single origin, and 36 percent reported having multiple ethnic origins, thus the overall total is greater than 100 percent.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Of the 36.3 million people enumerated in 2021, approximately 25.4 million reported being "White", representing 69.8 percent of the population.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The Indigenous population representing 5 percent or 1.8 million people, grew by 9.4 percent compared to the non-Indigenous population, which grew by 5.3 percent from 2016 to 2021.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Between 2011 and 2016, the visible minority population rose by 18.4 percent.
[src:canada/canada-p02] In 1961, about 300,000 people, less than two percent of Canada's population, were members of visible minority groups.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The 2021 census indicated that 8.3 million people, or almost one-quarter (23.0 percent) of the population, reported themselves as being or having been a landed immigrant or permanent resident in Canada—above the 1921 census previous record of 22.3 percent.
[src:canada/canada-p02] In 2021, India, China, and the Philippines were the top three countries of origin for immigrants moving to Canada.
[src:canada/canada-p02] A multitude of languages are used by Canadians, with English and French (the official languages) being the mother tongues of approximately 54 percent and 19 percent of Canadians, respectively.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada's official bilingualism policies give citizens the right to receive federal government services in either English or French with official-language minorities guaranteed their own schools in all provinces and territories.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Quebec's 1974 *Official Language Act* established French as the only official language of the province.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Although more than 82 percent of French-speaking Canadians live in Quebec, there are substantial Francophone populations in New Brunswick, Alberta, and Manitoba, with Ontario having the largest French-speaking population outside Quebec.
[src:canada/canada-p02] New Brunswick, the only officially bilingual province, has an Acadian French minority constituting 33 percent of the population.
[src:canada/canada-p02] There are also clusters of Acadians in southwestern Nova Scotia, on Cape Breton Island, and in central and western Prince Edward Island.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Other provinces have no official languages as such, but French is used as a language of instruction, in courts, and for other government services, in addition to English.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Manitoba, Ontario, and Quebec allow for both English and French to be spoken in the provincial legislatures and laws are enacted in both languages.
[src:canada/canada-p02] In Ontario, French has some legal status, but is not fully co-official.
[src:canada/canada-p02] There are 11 Indigenous language groups, composed of more than 65 distinct languages and dialects.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Several Indigenous languages have official status in the Northwest Territories.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Inuktitut is the majority language in Nunavut and is one of three official languages in the territory.
[src:canada/canada-p02] As of the 2021 census, just over 7.8 million Canadians listed a non-official language as their first language.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The country is also home to many sign languages, some of which are Indigenous.
[src:canada/canada-p02] American Sign Language (ASL) is used across the country due to the prevalence of ASL in primary and secondary schools.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Quebec Sign Language (LSQ) is used primarily in Quebec.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada is religiously diverse, encompassing a wide range of beliefs and customs.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The Constitution of Canada refers to God; however, Canada has no official church and the government is officially committed to religious pluralism.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Freedom of religion in Canada is a constitutionally protected right.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Rates of religious adherence have steadily decreased since the 1970s.
[src:canada/canada-p02] With Christianity in decline after having once been central and integral to Canadian culture and daily life, Canada has become a post-Christian, secular state.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Although the majority of Canadians consider religion to be unimportant in their daily lives, they still believe in God.
[src:canada/canada-p02] The practice of religion is generally considered a private matter.
[src:canada/canada-p02] According to the 2021 census, Christianity is the largest religion in Canada, with Roman Catholics representing 29.9 percent of the population having the most adherents.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Christians overall representing 53.3 percent of the population, are followed by people reporting irreligion or having no religion at 34.6 percent.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Other faiths include Islam (4.9 percent), Hinduism (2.3 percent), Sikhism (2.1 percent), Buddhism (1.0 percent), Judaism (0.9 percent), and Indigenous spirituality (0.2 percent).
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada has the second-largest national Sikh population, behind India.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Healthcare in Canada is delivered through the provincial and territorial systems of publicly funded health care, informally called Medicare.
[src:canada/canada-p02] It is guided by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984 and is universal.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Universal access to publicly funded health services "is often considered by Canadians as a fundamental value that ensures national healthcare insurance for everyone wherever they live in the country".
[src:canada/canada-p02] Around 30 percent of Canadians' healthcare is paid for through the private sector.
[src:canada/canada-p02] This mostly pays for services not covered or partially covered by Medicare, such as prescription drugs, dentistry and optometry.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Approximately 65 to 75 percent of Canadians have some form of supplementary health insurance; many receive it through their employers or access secondary social service programs.
[src:canada/canada-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Canada is experiencing an increase in healthcare expenditures due to a demographic shift toward an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:canada/canada-p02] In 2021, the average age in Canada was 41.9 years.
[src:canada/canada-p02] A 2016 report by the chief public health officer found that 88 percent of Canadians, one of the highest proportions of the population among G7 countries, indicated that they "had good or very good health".
[src:canada/canada-p02] Eighty percent of Canadian adults self-report having at least one major risk factor for chronic disease: smoking, physical inactivity, unhealthy eating or excessive alcohol use.
[src:canada/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest rates of adult obesity among OECD countries, contributing to approximately 2.7 million cases of diabetes.
